@Node "Installation" "MAB_english.guide/Installation"
@Toc "Main"

Installation
************

Simply click on the Installer icon on your first master disk. The
Installer will then ask you some questions, for example where you want
to install MainActor Broadcast. After the installation has completed,
please reset your Amiga to execute the necessary Assigns.  Afterwards,
you can start MainActor Broadcast like any other program.

   When you start MainActor Broadcast for the first time, a requester
appears, in which you must enter the serial number of your MainActor
Broadcast version. You can find it on your first master disk.


@EndNode

@Node "Introduction" "MAB_english.guide/Introduction"
@Toc "Main"

Introduction
************

   MainActor Broadcast is the official successor to MainActor, the
well-known modular animation package for the @{b}Amiga@{ub}.  MainActor
Broadcast is a not just only an 'enhanced version', but a complete new
program with a new user interface, a new module system and lots of new
modules and properties.

   The user interface of MainActor Broadcast is different from that of
MainActor, you can handle up to one hundred projects at the same time;
each project can have an animation, a picture or a picture list. All
projects are now displayed in one window, the @{i}Project Window@{ui}. With this
window, you can also underlay your animation with music and effects or
manipulate the time codes of the frames.

   The @{i}Control Window@{ui} controls the actions to be executed on the
animation or picture list, which is currently displayed in the @{i}Project
Window@{ui}. You can play the project, view single frames or get detailed
information about the whole project.  The @{i}Control Window@{ui} is also
responsible for loading and saving your projects.

   The @{i}Display Window@{ui} allows you to set the display parameters of your
projects.  You can select everything as you like, for example the
number of colours and the screen resolution of your project or how
often it should be played.

   The @{i}Text Buffer Window@{ui} gives you some information about the
currently executed action of MainActor Broadcast. This information is
buffered for enhanced clearness.


@EndNode

@Node "Starting Options" "MAB_english.guide/Starting Options"
@Toc "Main"

Starting Options
****************

   MainActor Broadcast can be started at two different ways: from the
Workbench or from the CLI.  When MainActor Broadcast is started from
the Workbench, the parameters are passed in form of @{b}Icon Tool Types@{ub};
when MainActor Broadcast is started from the CLI, you can directly give
the Parameters.


 @{" Starting from the Workbench " Link "Starting from the Workbench"} 
 @{" Starting from the CLI " Link "Starting from the CLI"} 


@EndNode

@Node "Starting from the Workbench" "MAB_english.guide/Starting from the Workbench"
@Toc "Starting Options"

Starting from the Workbench
===========================

MainActor Broadcast supports the following tool types:

@{b}NOGUI@{ub}
     This tool type tells MainActor Broadcast not to open it's graphic
     interface.  An icon is placed on the Workbench screen; with this
     icon, it is possible to open the graphic interface later.
     MainActor Broadcast can be controlled via ARexx, even when it's
     graphic interface is closed.

@{b}PUBSCREEN=<Name>@{ub}
     With this tool type, you can pass the name of the public screen,
     on which MainActor Broadcast should open it's graphic interface.

@{b}PORTNAME=<Name>@{ub}
     With this tool type, you can determine the name of MainActor
     Broadcast's global ARexx port.  Normally, this is @{b}MABROADCAST@{ub}.

@{b}STARTUP=<Start>@{ub}
     When you start MainActor Broadcast, it automatically executes the
     ARexx script named @{b}MABroadcast:Rexx/ Startup.ma@{ub}. You can change
     the name of that startup script with the @{i}STARTUP@{ui} tool type.


@EndNode

@Node "Starting from the CLI" "MAB_english.guide/Starting from the CLI"
@Toc "Starting Options"

Starting from the CLI
=====================

MainActor Broadcast supports the following commands:

@{b}NG=NOGUI/S@{ub}
     This option tells MainActor Broadcast not to open it's graphic
     interface.  Identical to the @{i}NOGUI@{ui} tool type.

@{b}PS=PUBSCREEN/K@{ub}
     With this option, you can pass the name of the public screen, on
     which MainActor Broadcast should open it's graphic interface.
     Identical to the @{i}PUBSCREEN@{ui} tool type.

@{b}PN=PORTNAME/K@{ub}
     Allows you to change the name of MainActor Broadcast's global
     ARexx interface.  Identical to the @{i}PORTNAME@{ui} tool type.

@{b}S=STARTUP/K@{ub}
     With this option, you can pass the name of the ARexx script
     MainActor Broadcast should execute when started. Identical to the
     @{i}STARTUP@{ui} tool type.


@EndNode

@Node "The Menus" "MAB_english.guide/The Menus"
@Toc "Main"

The Menus
*********

   This chapter describes the menus of MainActor Broadcast. You are
able to access most of MainActor Broadcast's functions through the
various menu items and their equivalent shortcuts.  Some functions can
only be accessed in the menus.


 @{" The Project Menu " Link "The Project Menu"}                   The Project Menu
 @{" The Selection Menu " Link "The Selection Menu"}                 The Selection Menu
 @{" The Miscellaneous Menu " Link "The Miscellaneous Menu"}             The Miscellaneous Menu
 @{" The Settings Menu " Link "The Settings Menu"}                  The Settings Menu
 @{" The Windows Menu " Link "The Windows Menu"}                   The Windows Menu


@EndNode

@Node "The Project Menu" "MAB_english.guide/The Project Menu"
@Toc "The Menus"

The Project Menu
================

@{b}New@{ub}
     This menu item opens an ASL requester, with which you can select
     the project to be opened.  This project is then loaded using the
     @{b}Universal@{ub} module.

@{b}Clear@{ub}
     This menu item closes the project currently active.

@{b}Switch left@{ub}
     With more than one project loaded, you can activate the project
     with the next lower number.

@{b}Switch right@{ub}
     With more than one project loaded, you can activate the project
     with the next higher number.

@{b}Iconify@{ub}
     Closes the graphic interface of MainActor Broadcast and places an
     icon on your Workbench. If you want to reactivate MainActor
     Broadcast's GUI, just click on the icon. You can make MainActor
     Broadcast execute ARexx scripts and commands in this inactive
     state.

@{b}About@{ub}
     Gives you some information about the current version of MainActor
     Broadcast and it's author.

@{b}Quit@{ub}
     Will close all windows and projects and quit MainActor Broadcast.


@EndNode

@Node "The Selection Menu" "MAB_english.guide/The Selection Menu"
@Toc "The Menus"

The Selection Menu
==================

   The @{i}Selection Menu@{ui} is very important for easy selection of the items
in your actual project. You can select and deselect all or a range of
items.  The menu items are only accessable if a project has been loaded.

@{b}Select All@{ub}
     Will select all items (frames/pictures) in your actual project.

@{b}Select Range@{ub}
     A window will pop up, in which you can enter the start and stop
     frame for the range of items to be selected.

@{b}Select Compression@{ub}
     Opens a window, in which you can enter the compression method for
     the range of items to be selected. You can display the compression
     method of a frame/picture with the @{i}Information Window@{ui}.

@{b}DeSelect All@{ub}
     This item will deselect all frames/pictures in your actual project.

@{b}DeSelect Range@{ub}
     A requester will pop up, in which you can enter the start/stop
     frame for the range of frames/pictures to be deselected.

@{b}DeSelect Compression@{ub}
     Opens a requester, in which you can enter the compression method
     for the range of items to be deselected. You can display the
     compression method of a frame/picture with the @{i}Information Window@{ui}.

@{b}Invert@{ub}
     Inverts the selection status of the items in the actual project.
     All selected items will become deselected and all deselected items
     will become selected.


@EndNode

@Node "The Miscellaneous Menu" "MAB_english.guide/The Miscellaneous Menu"
@Toc "The Menus"

The Miscellaneous Menu
======================

   See @{"The ARexx Interface" Link "The ARexx Interface"}, for more information of MainActor
Broadcast's ARexx capabilities.

@{b}Install ARexx Scripts@{ub}
     This menu item will open a window, in which you can map your most
     used ARexx scripts to the function keys; these will be
     automatically executed as you press the corresponding function key.

    @{b}function key@{ub}
          The cycle gadget in the upper part of the window will let you
          choose the function key on which you want to install an ARexx
          script.  The function keys are displayed as F1 ... F10.

    @{b}Shift@{ub}
          If this check box is activated, you must press the
          corresponding function key together with the @{b}Shift@{ub} key for
          the selected ARexx script to be executed. With the use of the
          @{b}Shift@{ub} key, MainActor Broadcast can manage up to 20 ARexx
          scripts.

    @{b}Select Script@{ub}
          Below the cycle gadget are the @{b}Select Script ...@{ub} gadget and a
          string gadget. The ARexx script, which is currently
          associated to the actual function key displayed in the cycle
          gadget, is visible in the string gadget.  You can enter a new
          ARexx script or edit the name of the existing one in the
          string gadget. You can use the @{b}Select Script ...@{ub} gadget to
          choose the ARexx script via an ASL requester.

          The three buttons in the lower part of the window are labeled
          @{b}Save@{ub}, @{b}Use@{ub} and @{b}Cancel@{ub}.

    @{b}Save@{ub}
          saves your definitions of the function keys, they will be
          automatically reloaded the next time you start MainActor
          Broadcast.

    @{b}Use@{ub}
          will keep the definitions, but will not save them.

    @{b}Cancel@{ub}
          ignores the changes you made to the definitions.

@{b}Print Text Buffer@{ub}
     Prints the information stored in the @{i}Text Buffer Window@{ui} on the
     actual printer.

@{b}Save Text Buffer As ...@{ub}
     Will let you choose a file into which the contents of the @{i}Text
     Buffer Window@{ui} will be saved.

@{b}Clear Text Buffer@{ub}
     Will clear the @{i}Text Buffer Window@{ui} and delete it's buffer.

@{b}Start ARexx Script@{ub}
     Will let you choose an ARexx script, which will then be executed
     by MainActor Broadcast.


@EndNode

@Node "The Settings Menu" "MAB_english.guide/The Settings Menu"
@Toc "The Menus"

The Settings Menu
=================

   With use of the @{i}Settings Menu@{ui}, you can configure the global settings
of MainActor Broadcast.

@{b}Select MABroadcast Screen@{ub}
     Choose the display mode for your MainActor Broadcast screen from
     the upcoming screen mode requester.

     Please note that the screen mode list contains some items of the
     form @{i}Window on XXXX Screen@{ui}.  These items cause MainActor Broadcast
     to open no screen of it's own, but to use a public screen, for
     example the Workbench screen, instead.

@{b}Select MABroadcast Font@{ub}
     Choose your font for MainActor Broadcast. This font will then be
     used for all windows, gadgets, menus. Only the list items of the
     @{"The Project Window" Link "The Project Window"} will be displayed in a different font, you can
     select it in the @{b}Select Project Font@{ub} menu item.

@{b}Select Project Font@{ub}
     Choose your font for the list items of the @{i}Project Window@{ui} of
     MainActor Broadcast.

@{b}Text Buffer Fill Bar@{ub}
     When this item is activated, the @{i}Text Buffer Window@{ui} contains a
     fill bar, which enlightens the period of the current action. You
     can abort the current action with the @{b}Cancel@{ub} key.

@{b}Create Index File@{ub}
     When this menu item is activated, MainActor Broadcast creates
     index files for the animations.  These index files contain
     information about the frames of the animation like size,
     compression method and offset in the file, etc. With an index file
     created, MainActor Broadcast can reload the corresponding
     animation much faster. The index files get the name of the
     animation with the suffix ".index".

@{b}Save icons for Animations/Pictures@{ub}
     MainActor Broadcast can optionally create icons when saving
     pictures or animations, if this menu item is activated. The tool
     types of the created icons correspond to the display settings of
     the former animation or pictures. As you click on the icon,
     MainView Broadcast is called to view the animation or picture.

@{b}Picture Lists@{ub}
     This menu item decides, wether you are able to load picture lists
     or not. If you only want to load single pictures, you better
     deactivate this item. When it is activated, you can load picture
     lists, as with MainActor, by using two ASL requesters, one
     defining the first and one defining the last picture.  All
     pictures, which lie lexicographicly between these two pictures,
     will be loaded into the current project.

@{b}Picture Sort Normal/Inverse@{ub}
     If the item @{b}Picture Lists@{ub} is activated, you can decide with this
     menu item, in which order the pictures should be sorted. As with
     MainActor, @{b}Normal@{ub} means, that the pictures are sorted
     lexicographicly while @{b}Inverse@{ub} sorts the other way. Let me give you
     an example: on your harddisk are ten pictures, named "test.00001"
     to "test.00010". You want to load these pictures as a picture list,
     so you choose "test.00001" in the first and "test.00010" in the
     second ASL requester. If @{b}Normal Picture Sort@{ub} is activated,
     MainActor Broadcast loads the pictures as following:

          test.00001
          test.00002
          test.00003
          test.00004
          ...
          test.00010

     If @{b}Inverse Picture Sort@{ub} is activated, MainActor Broadcast loads
     them as

          test.00010
          test.00009
          test.00008
          test.00007
          ...
          test.00001.

     The option @{b}Inverse Picture Sort@{ub} is very useful, if you want to
     create a ping pong animation.

@{b}Open Prefs@{ub}
     Opens an ASL requester which lets you choose a MainActor Broadcast
     preferences file, saved with one of the following menu items. When
     you have choosen a prefs file, the display AND all projects and
     their contents will be closed, MainActor Broadcast will then be
     reopened with the settings of the preferences file.

@{b}Save Prefs@{ub}
     Saves your current setup of MainActor Broadcast as the default
     preferences file, which will be automatically loaded when you
     start MainActor Broadcast. The default preferences file is
     @{b}MABroadcast:Prefs/Default_Prefs@{ub}. Nearly everything will be saved:
     the complete project information, all view settings, the actual
     project name, the size and position of all windows, the settings
     of the system preferences.

@{b}Save Prefs As...@{ub}
     You can of course not only store your actual settings as the
     default preferences file, but as every file you like. Just select
     the prefered file with the upcoming ASL requester.  An
     self-executing icon will be created for the preferences file. You
     should save every setup you use frequently!

@{b}Save at Exit@{ub}
     With this menu item selected, MainActor Broadcast will save it's
     actual settings as default when you leave the program. So, you
     will always find the same configuration when you start MainActor
     Broadcast as at the time you left it the last time.


@EndNode

@Node "The Windows Menu" "MAB_english.guide/The Windows Menu"
@Toc "The Menus"

The Windows Menu
================

   This menu will let you open/close the different MainActor Broadcast
windows by simply selecting the desired menu item. An activated menu
item means that the corresponding window is open, a deactivated that
the window is closed. The only exception is the @{i}Project Window@{ui}, it is
always open, when the graphic interface of MainActor Broadcast is
activated.


@EndNode

@Node "The Windows" "MAB_english.guide/The Windows"
@Toc "Main"

The Windows
***********

   The windows are MainActor Broadcast's main interface to the user.
Their use is however optional, you can close all of them (except the
@{i}Project Window@{ui}) and only use the menus. The choice is yours. The
position and status of the windows will be saved in the preferences
files.

   The following is a detailed description of MainActor Broadcast's
windows and their gadgets.


 @{" The Project Window " Link "The Project Window"}                 The Project Window
 @{" The Control Window " Link "The Control Window"}                 The Control Window
 @{" The Display Window " Link "The Display Window"}                 The Display Window
 @{" The Text Buffer Window " Link "The Text Buffer Window"}             The Text Buffer Window


@EndNode

@Node "The Project Window" "MAB_english.guide/The Project Window"
@Toc "The Windows"

The Project Window
==================

   The @{i}Project Window@{ui} shows the project currently active and gives
various possibilities of editing this project.

   The title bar of the @{i}Project Window@{ui} shows the number of the actual
project sepearated from the project name by a colon, like @{b}1:
SeaQuest.anim@{ub}.  If no project is loaded, the title is @{b}No Project loaded@{ub}.

   You can remove the actual project from memory by klicking on the
@{b}Clear Project@{ub} button. To the left and to the right of this button,
there are two arrow symbols.  These symbols are only activated, if more
than one project has been loaded. Klicking on the left arrow activates
the project with the next lower project number, clicking on the right
arrow activates the project with the next higher one. The two arrows
submit a comfortable way to cycle through all currently loaded projects.

   Within the @{b}Project Box@{ub} are all the buttons, which belong to the
actual project. The three buttons @{b}Sound@{ub}, @{b}TCodes@{ub} und @{b}Effect@{ub} will be
explained later in detail.  Below these three buttons, there is a radio
button, which allows you to toggle between two states deciding from
where the project gets it's data. When reloading the project, the @{b}Cache
Data@{ub} check box in the @{i}Control Window@{ui} determines the access state of the
new project.

@{b}Access from RAM@{ub}
     If this radio button is activated, the project is cached or is
     going to be cached in RAM.  This means, that playing animations is
     smoother, because accesssing RAM is much faster than accessing
     hard disks or CD-ROMs directly. The disadvantage of this access
     is, that the project can only be as large as the amount of
     physical memory.

     If you activate @{b}Access from RAM@{ub}, MainActor Broadcast tries to load
     all data for the actual project from the device into memory. If
     you do not have enough RAM to cache the complete project, @{b}Access
     from RAM@{ub} will automatically be disabled and @{b}Access from device@{ub}
     will be enabled.

@{b}Access from device@{ub}
     If this radio button is activated, the project's data is loaded
     directly from the device that it is located on, for example a hard
     disk or a CD-ROM. This Access is much slower than accessing memory,
     but the size of the project is not limited to the amount of
     physical memory. That means, that you can, for example, play
     animations of 200 MByte with only five MBytes of RAM.

@{b}The Scrolling Frames/Picture List@{ub}
     The scroll list will let you choose the frames or pictures you
     want to execute a certain operation on. If you have an animation
     loaded for this project window, the scroll list will show you the
     numbered frames of the animation along with their timecodes. If
     you have a picture list or a single picture loaded, the scroll
     list will show you the name(s) of the pictures.

     Just (de)select the frame/picture by clicking on it's text. For
     multiple selection do not release the mouse button and move over
     the items to be selected. The list will scroll if you come to the
     top or bottom border.

     With the @{b}Select Project Font@{ub} menu item, you can select a special
     font for the list in the @{i}Project Window@{ui} (The default is Topaz 8),
     See @{"The Settings Menu" Link "The Settings Menu"}.

   But now back to the three buttons in the upper part of the @{b}Project
Box@{ub} mentioned above.  Each of them opens a window, in which you can
adjust and modify a certain aspect of the current project.


 @{" The Sound Window " Link "The Sound Window"} 			The Sound Window
 @{" The Timecode Window " Link "The Timecode Window"} 			The Timecode Window
 @{" The Effect Window " Link "The Effect Window"} 			The Effect Window


@EndNode

@Node "The Sound Window" "MAB_english.guide/The Sound Window"
@Toc "The Project Window"

The Sound Window
----------------

   The @{i}Sound Window@{ui} allows you to overlay your actual project with
music or sound effects.  MainActor Broadcast's sound support is module
independent. That means that you can use the same sound information
file on every animation or picture format MainActor Broadcast supports.
The @{i}Sound Window@{ui} can be opened by clicking on the @{b}Sound@{ub} button of the
@{i}Project Window@{ui}.

   The @{i}Sound Window@{ui} consists of two boxes; in the upper box, the @{b}Set
Sound Effects Box@{ub}, you can create, copy, remove and test sound effects.
In the second box, the @{b}Sound Effect Settings Box@{ub}, you can modify the
settings of the effect currently activated.

   In the @{b}Set Sound Effects Box@{ub}, there exists a list with the active
sound effects.  By clicking on an entry of the list, it is activated
and the settings of the effect are shown in the @{b}Sound Effect Settings
Box@{ub}. A new sound effect can be generated with the @{b}New Sound@{ub} button.
Afterwards, a new sound effect titled @{b}Undefined@{ub} is added to the list.
If a sound effect is defined and you want to create a new sound with
the same settings, you can use the @{b}Copy@{ub} button.  A sound effect can be
removed fom the list with the @{b}Remove@{ub} button and tested with the @{b}Test@{ub}
button. @{b}Test@{ub} has the sound effect played with it's actual settings.

   In the @{b}Sound Effect Settings Box@{ub}, you can modify the settings of the
active sound effect with some gadgets. The first gadget contained here
is the @{b}Invoke Sound@{ub} cycle gadget.  This cycle gadget toggles two states:

@{b}Mix Sound Effect (Only Samples)@{ub}
     If this option is activated, the current sample will be mixed into
     the currently running background music. The background music will
     not be interrupted ! Using mix samples, you can add sound effects
     to .MODs or allow up to 4 samples to play at the same time. The
     size of the mix samples is limited to 128kb, also only IFF-8SVX
     samples can be used as mix samples.

@{b}First Time only@{ub}
     With this state activated, MainActor Broadcast plays the sound
     only once for the first time and not at any run of the animation.
     This is quite useful for music effects which are to accompany the
     animation; very often, a music effect plays much longer than the
     real animation and so, with endless loop animations, the music
     effect would be broken and always played from the beginning. With
     this state, the music runs continuously and smooth.

@{b}Every loop pass@{ub}
     In this state, the sound is played at any run of the animation.
     This is useful for sound effects accompaning one or a few single
     frames.

   With the next slider, you can adjust the loudness of the sound
effect; the volume scale reaches from 0 (no output) to 64 (maximum
volume).

   With the next slider, you can adjust the balance for the actual
sound effect. The balance scale reaches from -64 to 64; if the balance
is 0, the sound is played at the same volume on the left and the right
side. If the balance becomes negative, the left channels are played
louder, if the balance becomes positive, the right channel are played
louder.  The extremal values -64/64 mean, that only the left/right
channels can be heared.

   When you click on the @{b}Select Frame@{ub} button, a requester appears, in
which the frames/pictures of the current project are shown. Simply
select the frame/picture, at which the sound effect should start.

   Now you must only pass the name of the sound object with the @{b}Select
Sound Object@{ub} button. MainActor Broadcast automatically realizes the
type of the sound object and activates the corresponding sound module.
Simply click on the @{b}Test@{ub} Button to examine, how MainActor Broadcast
plays the sound effect.

   If you want to save the sound information for your project, just
leave the @{i}Sound Window@{ui} with the @{b}Use Sounds@{ub} button. MainActor Broadcast
then creates the corresponding '.sound' file.  The @{b}Cancel@{ub} button closes
the @{i}Sound Window@{ui} without saving the sound effects and their settings.

   Remember that the sound objects will have to be cached in Chip-RAM,
MainActor Broadcast does not yet support to play the sound objects
directly from your harddisk or CD-ROM.  The maximum amount of Chip-RAM
you can have is 2 MByte, so be careful which and how many samples you
use inside your animations.


@EndNode

@Node "The Timecode Window" "MAB_english.guide/The Timecode Window"
@Toc "The Project Window"

The Timecode Window
-------------------

   When you click on the @{b}Timecode@{ub} button of the @{i}Project Window@{ui}, the
@{i}Timecode Window@{ui} is opened. In this window, you can adjust the timecode
of the frames of your animation.  So, the @{b}TCodes@{ub} button can only be
activated, if the actual project contains an animation. Some animation
formats like DL do not support timecodes. With these animations, the
@{b}TCodes@{ub} button remains deactivated, too.

   The timecode of a frame describes, how long this frame should be
displayed when the animation is played. MainActor Broadcast stores the
timecode in 1/60 seconds.  A timecode of 1/60 displays the frame for
exactly 1/60 seconds, a timecode of 60/60 displays it for one second.
Various animation formats only support one timecode for the whole
animation. That means, that all frames have the same display period.
These timecodes are called @{b}global timecodes@{ub}, @{b}local timecodes@{ub} are those,
which are responsible for only one frame of the animation.

   The title of the @{i}Timecode Window@{ui} shows you, if the current animation
format supports local or only global timecodes.

   You can enter your preferred timecode in the numerical field inside
of the @{b}Timecode Box@{ub}. If the timecode is local, the timecode of all
selected frames of the actual project is adjusted to he new value. If
the timecode is global, the new value becomes the global timecode of
the project and with that, the timecodes of all frames are set to the
new value.


@EndNode

@Node "The Effect Window" "MAB_english.guide/The Effect Window"
@Toc "The Project Window"

The Effect Window
-----------------

   The effect modules allow you to overlay the active project with
effects and other image processing operations. The @{i}Effect Window@{ui} can be
used to select and configure the preferred effect. You can open the
@{i}Effect Window@{ui} with the @{b}Effect@{ub} button inside the @{i}Project Window@{ui}.

   If you want to activate the selected module, you must select the
@{b}Effect Active@{ub} check box to the right of the Module picker gadget.
Having done this, the effect and the remaining fields of the @{i}Effect
Window@{ui} become active.

   The Effect Project has the same size as the former project. If you
want to change this size, you can determine the new size with the @{b}Width@{ub}
and @{b}Height@{ub} input fields. The display boxes @{b}MinW@{ub} and @{b}MinH@{ub} determine the
minimal width and height of the Effect project. These values are
identical to the former values. For more information refer to the
Chapter @{b}Music and Effects@{ub}.

   With the @{b}Frames@{ub} input field, you can determine the amount of frames
in your effect project.

   The @{b}Edit Settings@{ub} picker gadget opens the graphic interface of the
selected effect. Here, the settings of the effect itself can be
adjusted. The effects and their settings are discussed in detail in the
chapter @{b}The Effect Modules@{ub}.


@EndNode

@Node "The Display Window" "MAB_english.guide/The Display Window"
@Toc "The Windows"

The Display Window
==================

   With the @{i}Display Window@{ui}, you can configure the graphic output of the
display modules. The display modules carry the name of the hardware
they support, the @{b}Amiga@{ub} display module for example shows each graphic
information on a native Amiga screen while the @{b}Picasso@{ub} display module
uses a Picasso screen etc.  For more detailed description of the
modules please refer to chapter @{b}The Display Modules@{ub}.

   You can get the name of the active display module from the @{b}Module@{ub}
display box inside the @{i}Display Window@{ui}. By clicking on the picker gadget
at the right of the Module display box, you get a list of the display
modules currently available, where you can select the preferred display
module according to your hardware.

   After loading a project, MainActor Broadcast changes the attributes
of the display module to the values of the new project. MainActor
Broadcast tries to find out the optimal settings for each project. If
you do not want MainActor Broadcast to change the display attributes,
for example if you want each project to be played on an Amiga HAM
screen, you can select the @{b}Lock Attributes@{ub} check box to the right of
the picker gadget mentioned above. With this check box activated
MainActor Broadcast does not change the display settings any more.

   With the @{b}Type@{ub} cycle gadget, you can select the display type. Most of
the modules only support one single display type: Show graphics on a
screen. The @{b}Amiga@{ub} display module instead supports more, it allows, for
example, graphics also been displayed in a window.

   In the @{b}Mode@{ub} display box, you can see the actual screen mode of the
current project. You can change the screen mode by clicking on the
picker gadget at the right of the @{b}Mode@{ub} display box. The screen mode
determines the width and height of the new screen to be opened.

   With the @{b}Colors@{ub} slider, you can adjust the number of colours the
graphic data should be displayed with. The maximum amount of colours
depends on the project's width and height, the screen mode and the
hardware the display module is based on: Standard Amigas support 2 to
64, with HAM6 4.096 colours; AGA Amigas support 2 to 256, in HAM8
262.144 colours, while graphic boards, like the Picasso, can display
65.536 (65K) or 16.777.216 (16M) colours. You can chose the number of
colours as you like, MainActor Broadcast automatically generates the
necessary colour tables for your preferred amount of colours.

   With the @{b}Special@{ub} cycle gadget, you can activate some special display
options for the actual display module, for example the Extra-Halfbrite
or HAM modes of the @{b}Amiga@{ub} display module. For detailed description of
the special capabilities of the display modules have a look in the
description of the particular display module.

   With the @{b}More...@{ub} picker gadget, you can open the @{i}Additional Display
Settings Window@{ui}. In this Window, you can adjust more settings for
displaying graphic data.


 @{" Additional Display Settings " Link "Additional Display Settings"} 


@EndNode

@Node "Additional Display Settings" "MAB_english.guide/Additional Display Settings"
@Toc "The Display Window"

Additional Display Settings
---------------------------

   The @{i}Additional Display Settings Window@{ui} can only be be opened through
the @{i}Display Window@{ui} and offers some more adjustments for displaying
graphic data.

   You can activate the @{b}Center@{ub} option by selecting the @{b}Center@{ub} check box
in the @{b}Offset Box@{ub}. With this option activated, MainActor Broadcast
aligns the graphic data to the center of the screen. Otherwise, you can
adjust the x and y Offsets from the lower left edge of the screen with
the corresponding input fields.

   In the @{b}Dither Box@{ub}, you can select the dither algorithm MainActor
Broadcast uses to enhance the display quality. Dithering is only
useful, if you want to display graphic data with more colours than the
screen it should be displayed on, for example if you want to display a
true colour picture with 16M colours on a 256 colour Amiga screen.  The
quality of the result of the particular dithering algorithm depends
heavily on the graphic data itself; you have to test the algorithms to
get the best result. We recommend the Floyd-Steinberg algorithm.

   You can decide how often your projects should be played in the
@{b}Repeat Box@{ub}. With the @{b}Endless@{ub} check box activated, MainActor Broadcast
repeats to play the projects infinitely. Otherwise, you can define the
number of repetitions in the input field @{b}Number@{ub}. If you want MainActor
Broadcast to play each project only once, just enter a 1 into the
@{b}Number@{ub} input field.

   In the @{b}Misc. Box@{ub} you can do some more settings:

@{b}Stop Playback@{ub}
     With this check box activated, MainActor Broadcast stops the
     playback of an animation after the first frame. You can continue
     the playback by pressing a key. This option is useful, if you want
     to record your animations on a video recorder; you can start
     recording after displaying the first frame and then continue
     playing the animation.

@{b}Frame Counter@{ub}
     If this check box is activated, a frame counter is displayed in
     the upper right corner of the screen. This frame counter always
     gives then number of the current frame.

@{b}Fixed Palette@{ub}
     This function uses a fixed palette for 8bit projects. This is very
     useful if your single-buffer animations (FLI/FLC/Picasso..)
     flicker due to changing palettes. If this is the case, play/save
     the project with this option enabled.

@{b}Ext. Palette@{ub}
     With this check box activated, you can enter the name of an IFF
     file in the input field below or select it with the ASL file
     requester after clicking on the picking gadget to the right. The
     colour palette of this IFF file will then be used for displaying
     the projects.


@EndNode

@Node "The Control Window" "MAB_english.guide/The Control Window"
@Toc "The Windows"

The Control Window
==================

   The @{i}Control Window@{ui} consists of three boxes, the @{b}Load Box@{ub}, the @{b}Save
Box@{ub} and the @{b}Action Box@{ub}


 @{" The Load Box " Link "The Load Box"} 
 @{" The Save Box " Link "The Save Box"} 
 @{" The Action Box " Link "The Action Box"} 


@EndNode

@Node "The Load Box" "MAB_english.guide/The Load Box"
@Toc "The Control Window"

The Load Box
------------

   In the @{b}Load Box@{ub}, you can select from two different buttons, which
start different load modules. These buttons carry the name of the
particular load module; you can start them by simply clicking on the
button with the left mouse button. If you want to change the load
module for one of the buttons, just click the cycle gadget located to
the right of the button and select your preferred module from the
upcoming list. The particular buttons store the name and the path of
the last corresponding project. These paths are saved within the
settings of MainActor Broadcast.

   The @{b}Cache Data@{ub} check box determines, if MainActor Broadcast loads
the graphic data of the project from RAM or directly from hard disk or
CD-ROM. You can adjust this setting for each project in the @{i}Project
Window@{ui} afterwards. For detailed description of buffering the data in
RAM have a look in the chapter @{i}The Project Window@{ui}.


@EndNode

@Node "The Save Box" "MAB_english.guide/The Save Box"
@Toc "The Control Window"

The Save Box
------------

   The @{i}Save Box@{ui}

   The @{b}Save Box@{ub} looks similar to the @{b}Load Box@{ub}. The two buttons activate
save modules instead of load modules, they carry the name of their
particular save module. As above, you can start them by simply clicking
on the button with the left mouse button. If you want to change the
save module for one of the buttons, just click the cycle gadget located
to the right of the button and select your preferred module from the
upcoming list. The two buttons automatically store the name and the
path of the last corresponding project, these paths are saved within
the settings of MainActor Broadcast, too.

   The @{b}Settings@{ub} check box inside of the @{b}Save Box@{ub} decides, whether a
window, the @{i}Animation/Picture Saver Settings Window@{ui} is opened every
time you save your project or not. Inside this Window, you can adjust
several settings for saving. With the @{b}Settings@{ub} box not activated,
MainActor Broadcast uses the settings of the last project; they are
saved with the global settings of MainActor Broadcast.

   Like stated above, the @{i}Animation Saver Settings Window@{ui} or @{i}Picture
Saver Settings Window@{ui} appears after clicking on the button of a saver
module, depending on you saving an animation or pictures.

   Let us first explain the contents of the @{i}Animation Saver Settings
Window@{ui}.  The @{i}Animation Saver Settings Window@{ui} consists of two boxes,
called the @{b}Color Palette Box@{ub}, the @{b}Number of Colors Box@{ub} and the @{b}Action
Box@{ub}.

   In the @{b}Color Palettes Box@{ub} you can adjust, how many colour palettes
should be created for the new animation. This is, of course, only
useful for animation with up to 256 colours, which need a colour
palette.

@{b}Intelligent Layout@{ub}
     With this option activated, MainActor Broadcast automatically
     decides, which frames of the animation need a new colour palette;
     these palettes will then be created.

@{b}One per Animation@{ub}
     Only one colour palette will be created and used fo the whole
     animation.

@{b}One per Frame@{ub}
     Every frame of the animation gets a colour palette of it's own.

   We recommend to use always the intelligent layout.

   The @{b}Create Loop Frames@{ub} check box describes, if loop frames should be
created for the animation. This is useful to create an endless loop
animation.

   The @{b}Number of Colors Box@{ub} defines the number of colours for the
animation.

@{b}Display@{ub}
     With this option active, the number of colours is taken from the
     settings of the @{i}Display Window@{ui}. The amount itself is given in
     brackets.

@{b}Original@{ub}
     The number of colours ist taken from the original project. The
     amount itself is given in brackets.

@{b}65K@{ub}
     The animation is saved with 65.536 (65K) colours.

@{b}16M@{ub}
     The animation is saved with 16.777.216 (16M) colours.

   You can save the animation by use of the @{b}Save Anim@{ub} button or abort
the operation by use of the @{b}Cancel@{ub} button inside of the @{b}Action Box@{ub}.

   The @{i}Picture Saver Settings Window@{ui} consists of three boxes, called the
@{b}Picture Index Box@{ub}, the @{b}Number of Colors Box@{ub} and the @{b}Action Box@{ub}.  The
@{b}Number of Colors Box@{ub} is identical to it's counterpart inside of the
@{i}Animation Saver Settings Window@{ui}. The @{b}Picture Index Box@{ub} describes the
index of the pictures, built from five figures and seperated from the
name by a decimal point.

@{b}Start with One@{ub}
     With this option activated, the first picture has the index
     ".00001"; the index increases by one per picture.

@{b}Project Indices@{ub}
     Each picture gets it's index from it's number in the original
     project. For example picture 57 gets the index ".00057".

@{b}Custom@{ub}
     With this radio button activated, you can enter the starting index
     inside of the input field below. The index increases by one per
     picture.

   You can save the pictures by use of the @{b}Save Pictures@{ub} button or
abort the operation by use of the @{b}Cancel@{ub} button inside of the @{b}Action
Box@{ub}.


@EndNode

@Node "The Action Box" "MAB_english.guide/The Action Box"
@Toc "The Control Window"

The Action Box
--------------

   The @{b}Action Box@{ub} consists of three buttons: @{b}Show@{ub}, @{b}Play@{ub} and @{b}Info@{ub}.


 @{" The Show Button " Link "The Show Button"} 
 @{" The Play Button " Link "The Play Button"} 
 @{" The Info Button " Link "The Info Button"} 


@EndNode

@Node "The Show Button" "MAB_english.guide/The Show Button"
@Toc "The Action Box"

The Show Button
...............

   Activating the @{b}Show@{ub} button will display all the frames/pictures you
have selected in the actual project's scroll list, beginning with the
first frame/picture. The frames/pictures will, of course, be shown
according to the settings of @{"The Display Window" Link "The Display Window"}.

   The following keys can be used to control the showing of the
pictures:

@{b}ESCAPE OR LEFT MOUSEBUTTON@{ub}
     will abort showing the pictures.

@{b}SPACE@{ub}
     will show the next picture you have selected. Exist no more
     selected pictures, displaying will end.


@EndNode

@Node "The Play Button" "MAB_english.guide/The Play Button"
@Toc "The Action Box"

The Play Button
...............

   Activating the @{b}Play@{ub} button will start playback of the actual
project. You can play animations, but also picture lists. The
animation/picture list will be, of course, played according to the
settings of @{"The Display Window" Link "The Display Window"}.

   The following keys can be used to control the playing of the
animation:

ESCAPE OR LEFT MOUSEBUTTON
     will abort playing the animation

RETURN
     will enable the timecodes you see in the scroll list of the source
     project.  This setting is activated each time playback is started
     (default).

THE FUNCTION KEYS
     are used to set the frame rate, they override the defaults.  You
     can reactivate the defaults by pressing @{b}RETURN@{ub}.

    F1
          sets the timecode to 1/60 Second (60 fps)

    F2
          sets the timecode to 2/60 Second (30 fps)

    F3
          sets the timecode to 3/60 Second (20 fps)

    F4
          sets the timecode to 4/60 Second (15 fps)

    F5
          sets the timecode to 5/60 Second (12 fps)

    F6
          sets the timecode to 10/60 Second (6 fps)

    F7
          sets the timecode to 20/60 Second (3 fps)

    F8
          sets the timecode to 40/60 Second (1.5 fps)

    F9
          sets the timecode to 60/60 Second (1 fps)

    F10
          sets the timecode to 120/60 Second (0.333 fps)

SPACE
     will stop playing the animation. While the animation is stopped
     you can use the @{b}TAB@{ub} key to flip to the next frame. Preessing @{b}SPACE@{ub}
     again will resume playing the project.


@EndNode

@Node "The Info Button" "MAB_english.guide/The Info Button"
@Toc "The Action Box"

The Info Button
...............

   This button opens the @{i}Information Window@{ui}, which should give you all
needed information about your current project. This window contains two
boxes, the upper one called @{b}Project Information@{ub} gives information about
the whole project while the lower one, called @{b}Frame Information@{ub}, gives
only information about a single frame or picture of the project.

   If some of the terms sound strange, have a look in the @{b}glossary@{ub}.

@{b}Modul Name@{ub}
     Gives the name of the load module of the current project and with
     that the animation or picture format. If an effect module has been
     activated, the field shows the name of the effect module.

@{b}Width, Height :@{ub}
     This line shows you the width and height of your project in pixels.

@{b}Number of Colors :@{ub}
     Shows you the number of colours of your project.

@{b}Special Flags :@{ub}
     This line shows you special attributes of the project (if there
     are any).  The flags can currently be:

    ---
          for no flags

    HAM
          for HAM pictures or animations

    EHB
          for Extra-Halfbrite images

@{b}Number of Pictures/Frames :@{ub}
     Shows you the number of frames in your animation or the number of
     pictures in your picture list (not containing loop frames).

@{b}Loop Frames :@{ub}
     Shows you the number of loop frames in your project

@{b}Color Palettes :@{ub}
     Shows you the number of colour palettes in your project

@{b}Size in Bytes :@{ub}
     Shows you the size of your animation or the total size of all
     pictures in your picture list in bytes.

@{b}Graphic Format@{ub}
     This line contains the graphic format of the project: chunky-pixel
     or bitmap based. chunky-pixel based formats are for example :
     GIF/FLI/FLC.  If you dont have a chunky-pixel device (like Retina
     or the Picasso-II), decompression time of these formats are
     higher, as they have to be converted to the Amiga's bitmap format.

   The @{b}Frame Information Box@{ub} contains a list of all frames/pictures in
the current project. Special Information is given for a single selected
entry of the list.

@{b}Compression@{ub}
     Informs you about the compression method used for the currently
     selected picture. For example @{b}ByteRun@{ub} for IFF images or @{b}Delta5@{ub} for
     IFF-Anim5 frames. Consider that the first frame of an IFF-AnimX
     animation mostly has an IFF-ByteRun image for the first frame.

@{b}Size in Bytes@{ub}
     This field shows the size of the currently selected picture or
     frame in bytes.

@{b}Color Palette@{ub}
     This field contains @{b}Yes@{ub} if the picture has a colour palette of
     it's own and @{b}No@{ub}, if it has no colour palette.


@EndNode

@Node "The Text Buffer Window" "MAB_english.guide/The Text Buffer Window"
@Toc "The Windows"

The Text Buffer Window
======================

   This window shows and buffers messages for feedback to the user.
These are, for example, error messages or information about the action
being currently executed.  Optionally, a fill bar is displayed to
enlighten the period of the current action.  To the fill bar belongs
the @{b}Cancel@{ub} button; if you click it while an action is executed, the
execution of that action (like loading an animation) is interrupted.

   See @{"The Miscellaneous Menu" Link "The Miscellaneous Menu"}, for more functions concerning the text
buffer like printing or saving it.


@EndNode

@Node "Music and Effects" "MAB_english.guide/Music and Effects"
@Toc "Main"

Music and Effects
*****************

   Two of the main changes in MainActor Broadcast are the effect
modules and the extensive sound support. These modules are described in
detail inside of chapter @{b}The Modules@{ub}; this chapter only gives a short
introduction and some hopefully helpful information.


 @{" Sound Support " Link "Sound Support"} 
 @{" The Effects " Link "The Effects"} 


@EndNode

@Node "Sound Support" "MAB_english.guide/Sound Support"
@Toc "Music and Effects"

Sound Support
=============

   You can link sound files to the project's frames inside of the @{i}Sound
Window@{ui}.  This is equal to the way you do in MainActor, but in MainActor
Broadcast, you have much more options. Besides that, you do not have to
select the sound module; MainActor Broadcast automatically realizes the
sound format, even if the file is packed with @{b}XPK@{ub} or @{b}Powerpacker@{ub}. The
files will then be decompressed in memory before playback.

   MainActor Broadcast saves the information about the associated
sounds in it's own file, named with the base name of the project and
the suffix ".Sound". For example, the sound information of the
animation "test_anim7" would be "test_anim7.Sound".

   This way of handling the sound information has one big advantage.
Some animation formats, like AVI, save the sound data to the same file
as the graphic data. That means, that you must create a complete new
animation, even if you have only changed the sound information.  That
can be a really annoying process, especially with very big animations.
If you, however, changed the sound information in MainActor Broadcast,
only the ".Sound" file will be written once again, the graphic data
remains untouched.


@EndNode

@Node "The Effects" "MAB_english.guide/The Effects"
@Toc "Music and Effects"

The Effects
===========

   The effect modules enable you to apply some special operations to
your actual project.  Some effect modules even work with more than one
project, the @{b}Sequencer Module@{ub}, for example, allow you to bind up to
five projects together to one new project.

   Having activated an effect module, your project's frame list
changes. The frames are now renamed and renumbered according to the
name of your effect module and the time code function becomes disabled.
So, you cannot allocate time codes to projects with activated effect
module; to do that, you must first save the new project to an animation.
Apart from that, you can handle the frames of the effect project like
the frames of the original project, that means that you can show single
frames, play the effect project, add sounds, etc.

   In the @{i}Effect Window@{ui}, you can adjust the width, height and the
number of frames of the effect project. Some effect modules create this
information automatically, the @{b}Sequencer Module@{ub}, for example,
calculates the number of frames of the effect project by addition of
the frames of the projects, which are linked together. You can change
the settings of some modules, however.

   You can always change the width and height of the effect project,
but the values must not be smaller than the original values of the
project (without use of the @{b}Scale Module@{ub}). This option might be useful
in some special situations.  Pretend you have a picture with a
resolution of 320x200 points and you intend to rotate the picture
around it's center. Then it happens, that the edges of the picture get
lost, because they leave the 320x200 screen. If you adjust the width
and height of the effect project to 640x480 points instead, the effect
project will fit on the screen.

   Consider, that the effects work the same for projects containing an
animation and projects containing pictures. The effect modules always
take the next frame of the original project as source for the next
frame of the effect project; if there are not enough frames in the
original project, the effect module starts with the first frame again.
This behavior of the effect modules enable you to slowly transform the
running animation to another one by use of the @{b}FadeToImage Module@{ub}.

   Refer to chapter @{b}The Modules@{ub} for detailed descriptions of the effect
modules.


@EndNode

@Node "The Modules" "MAB_english.guide/The Modules"
@Toc "Main"

The Modules
***********

   MainActor Broadcast uses various module types. The modules used most
often are the load and save modules, they allow you to load and save a
picture or animation format.

   The effect modules overlay the actual project with a special effect,
while the sound modules enable you to link sounds effects and music to
your project.


 @{" The Display Modules " Link "The Display Modules"} 
 @{" The Load-Save Modules " Link "The Load-Save Modules"} 
 @{" The Effect Modules " Link "The Effect Modules"} 
 @{" The Sound Modules " Link "The Sound Modules"} 


@EndNode

@Node "The Display Modules" "MAB_english.guide/The Display Modules"
@Toc "The Modules"

The Display Modules
===================

   The display modules define the interface between MainActor and the
particular display output device, the native Amiga display or a graphic
board. The name of the display module is equivalent to the name of the
related hardware.

   The display modules can be adjusted in the @{i}Display Window@{ui}. You
should first read this chapter to know, what the gadgets and buttons
mean.


 @{" The Amiga Display Module " Link "The Amiga Display Module"} 
 @{" The CyberGFX Display Module " Link "The CyberGFX Display Module"} 
 @{" The Merlin Display Module " Link "The Merlin Display Module"} 
 @{" The Picasso Display Module " Link "The Picasso Display Module"} 
 @{" The Retina Display Module " Link "The Retina Display Module"} 


@EndNode

@Node "The Amiga Display Module" "MAB_english.guide/The Amiga Display Module"
@Toc "The Display Modules"

The Amiga Display Module
------------------------

   The @{b}Amiga@{ub} display module redirects the output of the modules
directly to the native Amiga display.

   It distinguishes three display types, which you can set with the @{b}Type@{ub}
button inside of the @{i}Display Window@{ui}:

@{b}Full Screen@{ub}
     This display type is the quickest one MainActor Broadcast supports
     on the native Amiga display. It uses system conform @{b}views@{ub} to
     manage the output.  Unfortunately, some emulations (like the EGS
     emulation) have some problems with this display type.

@{b}Intuition Screen@{ub}
     This display type uses normal Amiga screens to manage the graphic
     output.  It is for the users of those emulations, which cannot use
     the @{b}Full Screen@{ub} display mode.

@{b}Intuition Window@{ub}
     This display type is the slowest one MainActor Broadcast supports
     on the native Amiga display; it displays the graphic data in a
     window on the MainActor Broadcast or any other public screen. Some
     people asked, why the output into an Intuition window is so slow
     and if that could not be implemented faster. So we want to give a
     little technical explaination according to that theme. If you are
     not interested in this detail, just skip to the next subsection.

     Animations up to 256 colours use a colour palette, which exactly
     defines the colours of that animation. So, each pixel of the
     animation, which belongs to the value 5 gets, for example, the
     colour red. The Workbench instead uses a colour palette of it's
     own, here the value 5 might belong to the colour green.  At that
     point, each pixel of the animation gets a new value corresponding
     to the value of the old colour palette in the new one. To manage
     this operation, the values of the animation must be chunky-pixel
     based; because most of the Amiga formats are pixel oriented, they
     must at first be converted to their chunky-pixel equivalent. The
     new colour information must then be reconverted into the pixel
     oriented format to be written into the pixel based intuition
     window. This is the reason, that chunky-pixel formats are much
     faster when played in a window than the pixel oriented ones,
     because the conversion steps between chunky-pixel formats and
     pixel oriented formats are not necessary. So it seems, that faster
     playback of animations in a window is not possible in the actual
     Workbench relase. If there, however, exists a Workbench with a
     display depth of 16 or 24 bit, which no longer needs colour
     palettes (RTG), playback would be much faster.

   The Amiga hardware supports some special modes to display graphic
information.  These modes can be adjusted with the @{b}Special@{ub} cycle gadget
inside of the @{i}Display Window@{ui}.

The following modes are supported by the @{b}Amiga@{ub} display module:

@{b}Color Map@{ub}
     Normal output of the graphic information with the based colour
     palette.

@{b}EHB@{ub}
     Extra Halfbrite Mode: Allows to display up to 64 colours
     simultaneously; the second 32 colours are the same as the first 32
     colours, but only "half as bright". This mode is not as important
     as the HAM mode and is only supported in LoRes resolutions on
     NonAGA Amigas.

@{b}HAM (or HAM6)@{ub}
     Hold and Modify Mode: Allows to display up to 4.096 colours
     simultaneously; This mode is on NonAGA Amigas only supported in
     LoRes resolutions; it is useful to put a lot of colours into an
     animation, which has to run very fast.

@{b}HAM8@{ub}
     Is an enhancement to the original HAM mode and allows to display
     up to 262.144 colours simultaneously; it can only be used on AGA
     Amigas and is, like HAM, very interesting for animations.

   The Amiga hardware is pixel oriented, which means, that all
chunky-pixel animation and picture are rather slow when displayed. You
can change that by saving the chunky-pixel based projects to pixel
oriented formats, for example the IFF-Anim5/7/8 formats.


@EndNode

@Node "The CyberGFX Display Module" "MAB_english.guide/The CyberGFX Display Module"
@Toc "The Display Modules"

The CyberGFX Display Module
---------------------------

   This module redirects the output of the modules directly to the
graphics board the CyberGraphics Emulation from Frank Mariak and Thomas
Sontowski is currently running on.

   Nearly all graphic boards are chunky-pixel oriented, so all
pixel-oriented animation formats like IFF-Anim5/7/8 are slower on the
board then on the native Amiga display.  With 8 bit animations, you can
get maximum performance by using chunky-pixel oriented formats like
FLI, FLC, Picasso, Merlin, Retina. So, you should convert all 8 bit
pixel-oriented formats to one of the chunky-pixel formats shown above.

   With 15/16/24 bit animations, things aren't as easy as with 8 bit
animations. Nearly all boards use different display options. Owners of
a Picasso, Merlin, Retina, CyberVision, Spectrum or Piccolo board
should use their particular animation format.

   Starting with v1.03 of MainActor Broadcast, the CyberGraphics
display module offers a window display type, which will display all
graphics in a window on the MAB screen in 8, 16 or 24 bit.


@EndNode

@Node "The Merlin Display Module" "MAB_english.guide/The Merlin Display Module"
@Toc "The Display Modules"

The Merlin Display Module
-------------------------

   This module redirects the output of the modules directly to the
Merlin board from ProDev.

   The Merlin is chunky-pixel oriented, so all pixel-oriented animation
formats like IFF-Anim5/7/8 are slower on the Merlin then on the native
Amiga display.  You can change that by saving the project to a
chunky-pixel format like FLI/FLC or the Merlin animation format.

   The Merlin animation format stores graphic data in 8/16/24 bit, the
animations can so be played very fast. We recommend that format for use
with the Merlin.


@EndNode

@Node "The Picasso Display Module" "MAB_english.guide/The Picasso Display Module"
@Toc "The Display Modules"

The Picasso Display Module
--------------------------

   This module redirects the output of the load/save modules directly
to the Picasso-II board from VillageTronic.

   The Picasso is chunky-pixel oriented, so all pixel-oriented
animation formats like IFF-Anim5/7/8 are slower on the Picasso then on
the native Amiga display.  You can change that by saving the project to
a chunky-pixel format like FLI/FLC or the Picasso animation format.

   The Picasso animation format stores graphic data in 8/16/24 bit, the
animations can so be played very fast. We recommend that format for use
with the Picasso.


@EndNode

@Node "The Retina Display Module" "MAB_english.guide/The Retina Display Module"
@Toc "The Display Modules"

The Retina Display Module
-------------------------

   This module redirects the output of the modules directly to the
Retina board from MacroSystems.

   The Retina is chunky-pixel oriented, so all pixel-oriented animation
formats like IFF-Anim5/7/8 are slower on the Retina then on the native
Amiga display.  You can change that by saving the project to a
chunky-pixel format like FLI/FLC or the Retina animation format.

   The Retina animation format stores graphic data in 8/16/24 bit, the
animations can so be played very fast. We recommend that format for use
with the Retina.


@EndNode

@Node "The Load-Save Modules" "MAB_english.guide/The Load-Save Modules"
@Toc "The Modules"

The Load/Save Modules
=====================


 @{" Universal " Link "Universal"} 

 MainActor Broadcast 1.04 supports the following animation and picture formats:

 @{" AVI " Link "AVI"} 
 @{" CyberVision " Link "CyberVision"} 
 @{" BMP " Link "BMP"} 
 @{" DL " Link "DL"} 
 @{" FLI " Link "FLI"} 
 @{" FLC " Link "FLC"} 
 @{" GIF " Link "GIF"} 
 @{" IFF " Link "IFF"} 
 @{" IFF-Anim3 " Link "IFF-Anim3"} 
 @{" IFF-Anim5 " Link "IFF-Anim5"} 
 @{" IFF-Anim7 " Link "IFF-Anim7"} 
 @{" IFF-Anim8 " Link "IFF-Anim8"} 
 @{" IFF-AnimBrush " Link "IFF-AnimBrush"} 
 @{" IFF-AnimJ " Link "IFF-AnimJ"} 
 @{" JPEG " Link "JPEG"} 
 @{" Merlin " Link "Merlin"} 
 @{" MultiPic " Link "MultiPic"} 
 @{" PCX " Link "PCX"} 
 @{" Picasso " Link "Picasso"} 
 @{" Piccolo " Link "Piccolo"} 
 @{" QT " Link "QT"} 
 @{" Retina " Link "Retina"} 
 @{" Spectrum " Link "Spectrum"} 


@EndNode

@Node "Universal" "MAB_english.guide/Universal"
@Toc "The Load-Save Modules"

Universal
---------

   The @{b}Universal Modul@{ub} is a special meta module. It does not load a
special animation or picture format, but automatically recognizes,
which load module it should use with the actual project. So you do not
have to adjust your load module every time you use another file format.


@EndNode

@Node "AVI" "MAB_english.guide/AVI"
@Toc "The Load-Save Modules"

AVI
---

   AVI is the animation format used by @{b}Video for Windows@{ub} on IBM
compatible computers, done by Microsoft. It is chunky-pixel based,
usually sound information is fixed to the graphic data. You can save
the audio data as IFF sample or play it directly from the AVI file with
the program @{b}RipAVISound@{ub}; have a look at the chapter @{b}RipAVISound@{ub} to get
details.

Currently, MainActor Broadcast supports AVI files with one of the
following compression methods:

   @{b}*@{ub} CRAM (8/16 bit)

   @{b}*@{ub} RLE (8 bit)

   @{b}*@{ub} BI_RGB (8/16/24 bit)

   @{b}*@{ub} CVID (24 bit)

   @{b}*@{ub} ULTI (16 bit)

   If the compression method of an AVI file should not be recognized by
MainActor Broadcast, the Information Window states compression @{b}UNKNOWN@{ub}.


@EndNode

@Node "BMP" "MAB_english.guide/BMP"
@Toc "The Load-Save Modules"

BMP
---

   This file format was designed by Microsoft and is heavily used on
the PC, especially under Windows and OS/2.  MainActor Broadcast is able
to read and write 2/4/8/24 Bit BMP files, packed and unpacked.


@EndNode

@Node "CyberVision" "MAB_english.guide/CyberVision"
@Toc "The Load-Save Modules"

CyberVision
-----------

   This animation format was especially created for the CyberVision
graphic board from Phase5. The modules can handle resolutions of
8/16/24 bit, the preferred display depth is 16 bit. 16-Bit is faster
than 24-Bit and offers nearly the same image quality, so you should
give it a try. You must have the CyberGraphics display module activated
to get the most of this animation format.


@EndNode

@Node "DL" "MAB_english.guide/DL"
@Toc "The Load-Save Modules"

DL
--

   DL animations are chunky-pixel based and dont support data crunching.
MainActor Broadcast supports type 1 and type 2 DL animations. Type 1
animations are fixed to an resolution of 160*100, type 2 animations can
contain resolutions of 320*200, 160*100 and 80*50. The image depth is
fixed to 8 bit.


@EndNode

@Node "FLI" "MAB_english.guide/FLI"
@Toc "The Load-Save Modules"

FLI
---

   FLI animations are created by Animator Pro, an animation program
only available on PC computers.  It is quite old, it can only contain
320*200 animations and its depth is fixed to 8 bit. The successor of
FLI is FLC. I have included the FLI modules for use with MainActor
Broadcast, because a lot of animations (especially on CD-ROM) are in
this format.

Pecularities:

   @{b}*@{ub} FLI animations have only one (global) timecode, it applies to all
     frames of the animation. You will therefore only be able to set
     the global timecode and will not set a timecode per frame as usual.

   @{b}*@{ub} Because of the missing timecode per frame feature, a lot of
     animations contain 'Dummy' frames. These are empty frames who
     shall time the animations.  N Dummy frames will, for example,
     delay the playback of the animation for N * global timecode. You
     can recognize Dummy frames in the @{i}Information Window@{ui}, they have a
     bytesize of '0' and a compression type of 'Dummy'.


@EndNode

@Node "FLC" "MAB_english.guide/FLC"
@Toc "The Load-Save Modules"

FLC
---

   FLC animations are created by Animator Pro, an animation program
only available on PC computers.  FLC is the successor of FLI. FLC
animations are not fixed to 320*200 resolutions like FLI and have
faster DELTA chunks.

Pecularities:

   @{b}*@{ub} FLC animations have only one (global) timecode, it applies to all
     frames of the animation. You you will therefore only be able to
     set the global timecode and will not set a timecode per frame as
     usual.

   @{b}*@{ub} Because of the missing timecode per frame feature, a lot of
     animations contain 'Dummy' frames. These are empty frames who
     shall time the animations.  N Dummy frames will for example delay
     the playback of the animation for N * global timecode. You can
     recognize Dummy frames in the @{i}Information Window@{ui}, they have a
     bytesize of '0' and a compression type of 'Dummy'.


@EndNode

@Node "GIF" "MAB_english.guide/GIF"
@Toc "The Load-Save Modules"

GIF
---

   A widely spread image format, designed by @{b}CompuServe@{ub}. Revisions 87A
and 89A are supported. The display depth is limited to 8 bit.


@EndNode

@Node "IFF" "MAB_english.guide/IFF"
@Toc "The Load-Save Modules"

IFF
---

   IFF ist an abbreviation for Interchangeable File Format; this
specification is the standard file format for the Amiga and was
designed by @{b}Electronic Arts@{ub}. IFF pictures can have display depths of
1-8 and 24 bit.


@EndNode

@Node "IFF-Anim3" "MAB_english.guide/IFF-Anim3"
@Toc "The Load-Save Modules"

IFF-Anim3
---------

   The opcode 3 animation format is very old. I did find some old
Tobias Richter animations which used this format and decided to support
it.

Pecularities:

   @{b}*@{ub} Some odd sized animations can cause trouble on AGA machines as
     opcode3 animations assume that the bitmap width should only be
     divideable by 8. AGA machines in higher fetchmodes need bitmaps
     which are divideable by 32/64; if you experience this, your only
     chance is to avoid higher fetchmodes by selecting a (PAL/NTSC)
     LowRes display.


@EndNode

@Node "IFF-Anim5" "MAB_english.guide/IFF-Anim5"
@Toc "The Load-Save Modules"

IFF-Anim5
---------

   The IFF-Anim5 specification was created by @{b}Electronic Arts@{ub}. It is a
"good at compressing but slow at playing" format. It is the slowest of
all IFF animation formats, because it saves the data as bytes.


@EndNode

@Node "IFF-Anim7" "MAB_english.guide/IFF-Anim7"
@Toc "The Load-Save Modules"

IFF-Anim7
---------

   The IFF-Anim7 specification was created by @{b}Wolfgang Hofer@{ub}. It is a
quite good compromise between speed and animation size. The
IFF-Anim7_16 modules use words (16 bits), the Anim-7_32 modules
longwords (32 bits) for compression. Therefore the 16 bit variant
compresses slightly better than the 32 bit modules, but playback is
slower.

   The IFF-Anim7_32 modules are, in my opinion, the best choice for
timeable, fast animations.

Pecularities:

   @{b}*@{ub} Make sure that the width of the animation is divideable by 16 for
     IFF-Anim7_16 animations or 32 for IFF-Anim7_32 anims.  Otherwise
     you will see a small area to the right of the screen which will
     not be updated correctly.


@EndNode

@Node "IFF-Anim8" "MAB_english.guide/IFF-Anim8"
@Toc "The Load-Save Modules"

IFF-Anim8
---------

   The IFF-Anim8 specification was created by Joe Porkka of formerly
@{b}ASDG@{ub} (now: @{b}Elastic Reality@{ub}) and is comparable to the IFF-Anim7 modules.

Pecularities:

   @{b}*@{ub} Make sure that the width of the animation is divideable by 16 for
     IFF-Anim8_16 animations or 32 for IFF-Anim8_32 anims.  Otherwise
     you will see a small area to the right of the screen which will
     not be updated correctly.


@EndNode

@Node "IFF-AnimBrush" "MAB_english.guide/IFF-AnimBrush"
@Toc "The Load-Save Modules"

IFF-AnimBrush
-------------

   The IFF-AnimBrush specification was created by @{b}Dan Silva@{ub} (the author
of Deluxe Paint) of Electronic Arts.  Anim Brushes are, of course,
used/saved by Deluxe Paint.

Pecularities:

   @{b}*@{ub} There is no save module at the moment.


@EndNode

@Node "IFF-AnimJ" "MAB_english.guide/IFF-AnimJ"
@Toc "The Load-Save Modules"

IFF-AnimJ
---------

   The IFF-AnimJ (.movie) format was created by @{b}Eric Graham@{ub}, who also
made the famous Juggler demo. The Juggler, in fact, is an IFF-AnimJ
animation.

Pecularities:

   @{b}*@{ub} This animation format is quite old and is supported for nostalgic
     reasons only.


@EndNode

@Node "JPEG" "MAB_english.guide/JPEG"
@Toc "The Load-Save Modules"

JPEG
----

   The JPEG format has meanwhile established a quasi standard for
pictures.  The graphic information can only be stored in true colour
(24 bit).  MainActor Broadcast uses the JPEG codec of @{b}Christoph Fleck@{ub}.

About the JPEG codec
-------------------
This application uses the "Tower JPEG Codec Class" for JPEG support.
The JPEG codec is Copyright © 1994 Christoph Feck, TowerSystems.  All
Rights Reserved.  It is based in part on the work of the Independent
JPEG Group.

   The JPEG codec is provided "AS-IS" and subject to change without
prior notice; no warranties are made.  All use is at your own risk.  No
liability or responsibility is assumed.


@EndNode

@Node "Merlin" "MAB_english.guide/Merlin"
@Toc "The Load-Save Modules"

Merlin
------

   This animation format was especially created for the Merlin graphic
board.  The modules can handle resolutions of 8/16/24 bit, the
preferred display depth is 16 bit. 16-Bit is faster than 24-Bit and
offers nearly the same image quality so you should give it a try.


@EndNode

@Node "MultiPic" "MAB_english.guide/MultiPic"
@Toc "The Load-Save Modules"

MultiPic
--------

   This module supports the multipic library from MacroSystems.

   The multipic.library supports a few picture formats, like JPEG, BMP,
VLAB etc.  The Universal Module only activates the MultiPic Module, if
MainActor Broadcast itself doesn't recognize the picure format.


@EndNode

@Node "PCX" "MAB_english.guide/PCX"
@Toc "The Load-Save Modules"

PCX
---

   PCX is a picture format heavily used on PC's, it was designed by
@{b}ZSoft@{ub}. MainActor Broadcast can handle 24 Bit PCX files.


@EndNode

@Node "Picasso" "MAB_english.guide/Picasso"
@Toc "The Load-Save Modules"

Picasso
-------

   This animation format was especially created for the Picasso graphic
board from VillageTronic. The modules can handle resolutions of 8/16/24
bit, the preferred display depth is 16 bit. 16-Bit is faster than
24-Bit and offers nearly the same image quality, so you should give it
a try.


@EndNode

@Node "Piccolo" "MAB_english.guide/Piccolo"
@Toc "The Load-Save Modules"

Piccolo
-------

   This animation format was especially created for the Piccolo SD64
(Classic) graphic board from Ingenieurbüro Helfrich. The modules can
handle resolutions of 8/16/24 bit, the preferred display depth is 16
bit. 16-Bit is faster than 24-Bit and offers nearly the same image
quality, so you should give it a try. You must have the CyberGraphics
display module activated to get the most of this animation format.


@EndNode

@Node "QT" "MAB_english.guide/QT"
@Toc "The Load-Save Modules"

QT
--

   Quicktime (QT) is an animation format heavily used on Apple McIntosh
computers. The sound information in Quicktime animations are currently
not supported.

The following compression methods are currently supported:

   @{b}*@{ub} RLE (1/8/16/24 bit)

   @{b}*@{ub} CVID (24 bit)

   @{b}*@{ub} RPZA (16 bit)

   @{b}*@{ub} SMC (8 bit)

   If the compression method of an QT file should not be recognized by
MainActor Broadcast, the @{i}Information Window@{ui} states compression @{b}UNKNOWN@{ub}.


@EndNode

@Node "Retina" "MAB_english.guide/Retina"
@Toc "The Load-Save Modules"

Retina
------

   This animation format was especially created for the Retina and
Retina Z-III graphic boards from @{b}MacroSystems@{ub}. The modules can handle
resolutions of 8/16/24 bit, the preferred display depth is 16 bit.
16-Bit is faster than 24-Bit and offers nearly the same image quality,
so you should give it a try.


@EndNode

@Node "Spectrum" "MAB_english.guide/Spectrum"
@Toc "The Load-Save Modules"

Spectrum
--------

   This animation format was especially created for the Spectrum
graphic board from GVP. The modules can handle resolutions of 8/16/24
bit, the preferred display depth is 16 bit. 16-Bit is faster than
24-Bit and offers nearly the same image quality, so you should give it
a try. You must have the CyberGraphics display module activated to get
the most of this animation format.


@EndNode

@Node "The Effect Modules" "MAB_english.guide/The Effect Modules"
@Toc "The Modules"

The Effect Modules
==================

   This section describes the characteristics of the effect modules and
is thought as reference. Besides, the graphic user interface and the
ARexx interface of the modules will be explained.

All effect modules use the following Arexx arguments:

@{b}Template@{ub}
     WIDTH/K,HEIGHT/K,FRAMES/K

   WIDTH and HEIGHT give the dimensions of the effect projekt, FRAMES
it's number of frames. These values can be adjusted by usage of the
graphic interface of the @{i}Effect Window@{ui}.


 @{" 3D-Stars " Link "3D-Stars"} 
 @{" Background " Link "Background"} 
 @{" FadeToColor " Link "FadeToColor"} 
 @{" FadeToImage " Link "FadeToImage"} 
 @{" FourInOne " Link "FourInOne"} 
 @{" Rotate " Link "Rotate"} 
 @{" Scale " Link "Scale"} 
 @{" ScrollIn " Link "ScrollIn"} 
 @{" ScrollOut " Link "ScrollOut"} 
 @{" Sequencer " Link "Sequencer"} 
 @{" Text " Link "Text"} 
 @{" Wipe_Squares " Link "Wipe_Squares"} 


@EndNode

@Node "3D-Stars" "MAB_english.guide/3D-Stars"
@Toc "The Effect Modules"

3D-Stars
--------

@{b}ARexx template@{ub}
     SPEED/K,NUMBERS/K

   The @{i}3D-Stars@{ui} effect module creates a 3D starry sky. The stars seem
to fly from deep space onto the observer. You can adjust the speed of
the stars with the graphic interface. The @{b}Speed@{ub} input field sets the
speed the stars move with in space.  The related ARexx argument is
@{b}SPEED@{ub}; the speed can have values from 1 to 16.

   Besides, the number of stars can be set in the graphic interface.
The related ARexx argument is @{b} NUMBERS@{ub}.

   Remember that the @{b}3D-Stars@{ub} effect module adds 4 grey colours to the
colour list of the effect project. Do these colours not fit into the
project's colour map, you must increase the number of colours by 4.

   If you want to create a pure starry sky you simply load the
"BlackFrame" picture from the directory "@{b}ABroadcast:Pictures@{ub}" and
overlay it with the @{i}3D-Stars@{ui} effect.


@EndNode

@Node "Background" "MAB_english.guide/Background"
@Toc "The Effect Modules"

Background
----------

@{b}ARexx template@{ub}
     PR=PROJECTNUMBER/K,R=RED/K,G=GREEN/K,
     B=BLUE/K

   The @{i}Background@{ui} effect module offers you to put another project into
the background of the actual project. This is equivalent to a genlock
effect, which means, that the background project can only be seen in a
special colour of the foreground project, named the background colour
(most of all the colour black).

   Imagine you want to overlay your project with a logo. That logo has
the colour white, it's background is black. Now you want to see your
animation at evry place that is not hidden by the logo. In this case
you would simply define the logo as the foreground project and the
animation as the background project. The colour black would then be the
perfect genlock colour.

   You can define the background project by editing the number of the
project in the @{b}Project Nr@{ub} input field inside of the graphic interface.
Besides you can adjust the RGB values of the genlock colour exactly
with the @{b}Red@{ub}, @{b}Green@{ub} and @{b}Blue@{ub} sliders.

   The two projects must have the same width and height, the background
project may not have an effect of it's own.

   With ARexx, you define the Background Project by the
@{b}PROJECTNUMBER@{ub} argument; with the @{b}RED@{ub}, @{b}GREEN@{ub} and @{b}BLUE@{ub} argument, you pass
the RGB values of the background colour.


@EndNode

@Node "FadeToColor" "MAB_english.guide/FadeToColor"
@Toc "The Effect Modules"

FadeToColor
-----------

@{b}ARexx template@{ub}
     FS=FADESTEPS/K,R=RED/K,G=GREEN/K,
     B=BLUE/K

   The @{i}FadeToColor@{ui} effect module fades the actual project to the
selected colour.

   The number of frames between the first frame of the effect project,
the frame in the original project and the last frame, the selected
colour, can be adjusted in the @{b}Fade Steps@{ub} input field inside of the
graphic interface. The equivalent ARexx argument is @{b}FADESTEPS@{ub}.

   Since the fade steps only contain the intermediate frames, the
effect module adds two more frames for the first and the last frame
being the frame to fade from the original project and the colour.

   You can adjust the RGB values of the prefered fade colour exactly
with the @{b}Red@{ub}, @{b}Green@{ub} and @{b}Blue@{ub} sliders inside of the graphic interface or
pass the RGB values of the fade colour with the @{b}RED@{ub}, @{b}GREEN@{ub} and @{b}BLUE@{ub}
ARexx argument.


@EndNode

@Node "FadeToImage" "MAB_english.guide/FadeToImage"
@Toc "The Effect Modules"

FadeToImage
-----------

@{b}ARexx template@{ub}
     PR=PROJECTNUMBER/K,FS=FADESTEPS/K

   The @{i}FadeToImage@{ui} effect module fades the actual project to another
project. This works similar to the @{i}FadeToColor@{ui} effect module with the
final frame of the effect project not being a single colour but the
momentary frame in the selected destination project.

   The number of frames between the first frame of the effect project,
the frame in the original project and the last frame, the selected
colour, can be adjusted in the @{b}Fade Steps@{ub} input field inside of the
graphic interface. The equivalent ARexx argument is @{b}FADESTEPS@{ub}.

   Since the fade steps only contain the intermediate frames, the
effect module adds two more frames for the first and the last frame
being the frame to fade from the original project and the frame to fade
to fom the destination project.

   You can define the background project by editing the number of the
destination project in the @{b}Project Nr@{ub} input field inside of the graphic
interface. The two projects must have the same width and height, the
destination project may not have an effect of it's own.

   With ARexx, you define the background project by the
@{b}PROJECTNUMBER@{ub} argument.


@EndNode

@Node "FourInOne" "MAB_english.guide/FourInOne"
@Toc "The Effect Modules"

FourInOne
---------

@{b}ARexx template@{ub}
     P2=PROJECT2/K,P3=PROJECT3/K,
     P4=PROJECT4/K

   The @{i}FourInOne@{ui} effect module combines up to four projects to run
simultaneously on one screen. The source project is always the one in
the @{i}Project Window@{ui}. You can combine the projects as you like, for
example with two projects arranged vertically or horizontally.

   You can define the four projects by entering their project numbers
in the input field iside of the graphic interface. With ARexx, you can
use the @{b}PROJECT2@{ub}, @{b}PROJECT3@{ub} and @{b}PROJECT4@{ub} arguments to set the particular
projects.

   The projects must all have the same width and height,


@EndNode

@Node "Rotate" "MAB_english.guide/Rotate"
@Toc "The Effect Modules"

Rotate
------

@{b}ARexx template@{ub}
     X/K,Y/K,Z/K,INCX/K,INCY/K,INCZ/K

   The @{i}Rotate@{ui} effect module offers you to rotate your project around
the x, y and z axis. You can adjust the initial rotate values and the
increase factor for every axis with the slider bars in the @{b}Rotate
Settings Box@{ub} and the @{b}Increase Settings Box@{ub} inside of the graphic
interface. The rotation values will be increased by the increase factor
with every frame of the effect project.

   If you reset all values to 0 and adjust the slider bar of the x
increase value to 10, the picture slowly rotates around the x axis. You
will need 37 frames to manage a full 360 degree rotation in this
example.

   With positive values the project rotates clockwise, with negative
ones counterclockwise.

   You can pass the initial rotation values with the @{b}X@{ub}, @{b}Y@{ub} and @{b}Z@{ub} ARexx
arguments; the @{b}INCX@{ub}, @{b}INCY@{ub} and @{b}INCZ@{ub} arguments refer to the increase
values.


@EndNode

@Node "Scale" "MAB_english.guide/Scale"
@Toc "The Effect Modules"

Scale
-----

@{b}ARexx template@{ub}
     SCALEWIDTH/K,SCALEHEIGHT/K,
     PERCENTINCREASE/K

   The @{i}Scale@{ui} effect module scales the frames of the actual project to a
new size.  Just enter the new value for the width in the @{b}Width@{ub} input
field and the new value for the height in the @{b}Height@{ub} input field inside
of the graphic interface. To the right of these two input fields, the
display boxes @{b}Original Width@{ub} and @{b}Original Height@{ub} show the dimensions of
the original project.

   You can also pass the new width and height of the effect project
with the @{b}SCALEWIDTH@{ub} and @{b}SCALEHEIGHT@{ub} ARexx arguments.

   You can enter the new dimensions in comparison with the original
ones by usage of the @{b}PercW@{ub} and @{b}PercH@{ub} input fields or their related
slider bars.  For example, 100 percent Width is the original width, 50
percent only the half and 200 percent twice as much.

   You can also get the values 50, 100 and 200 percent by usage of the
three buttons @{b}50@{ub}, @{b}100@{ub} and @{b}200@{ub} at the bottom of the @{b}Scale Box@{ub} inside of
the graphic interface.

   The last input field inside of the graphic interface is the @{b}Increase@{ub}
input field with it's related slider bar. You can use it to define the
value the project increases or decreases from frame to frame. If you
want to zoom your project to the screen, set the initial dimension of
the project to a very small value (1 percent for width and height) and
adjust the increase value to 2 percent. The project will then slowly
zoom to the observer.

   You can pass the increase value with the @{b}PERCENTINCREASE@{ub} ARexx
argument.

   Please notice, that you automatically enlarge the dimension of the
project's screen if you enlarge the dimension of the effect project. If
you reduce the size of the effect project, the screen size is not
reduced. You must do that manually in the @{i}Effect Window@{ui}.


@EndNode

@Node "ScrollIn" "MAB_english.guide/ScrollIn"
@Toc "The Effect Modules"

ScrollIn
--------

@{b}ARexx template@{ub}
     DIR=DIRECTION/K,SS=SCROLLSTEPS/K

   The @{i}ScrollIn@{ui} effect module scrolls the project from the left, the
right, the top or the bottom inside the screen. You can determine the
direction with the radio buttons @{b}Top@{ub}, @{b}Bottom@{ub}, @{b}Left@{ub} and @{b}Right@{ub} and the
number of scroll steps in pixels with the @{b}Scroll Steps@{ub} input field
inside of the graphic interface. The last one describes the interation
value of the scroll operation.

   With ARexx, you can pass the direction with the @{b}DIRECTION@{ub} argument
and one of the keywords @{b}TOP@{ub}, @{b}BOTTOM@{ub}, @{b}LEFT@{ub} or @{b}RIGHT@{ub}. The @{b}SCROLLSTEPS@{ub}
argument passes the iteration factor of the scroll operation.


@EndNode

@Node "ScrollOut" "MAB_english.guide/ScrollOut"
@Toc "The Effect Modules"

ScrollOut
---------

@{b}ARexx template@{ub}
     DIR=DIRECTION/K,SS=SCROLLSTEPS/K

   The @{i}ScrollOut@{ui} effect module scrolls the project to the left, right,
top or bottom outside of the screen. You can determine the direction
with the radio buttons @{b}Top@{ub}, @{b}Bottom@{ub}, @{b}Left@{ub} and @{b}Right@{ub} and the number of
scroll steps in pixels with the @{b}Scroll Steps@{ub} input field inside of the
graphic interface. The last one describes the interation value of the
scroll operation.

   With ARexx, you can pass the direction with the @{b}DIRECTION@{ub} argument
and one of the keywords @{b}TOP@{ub}, @{b}BOTTOM@{ub}, @{b}LEFT@{ub} or @{b}RIGHT@{ub}. The @{b}SCROLLSTEPS@{ub}
argument passes the iteration factor of the scroll operation.


@EndNode

@Node "Sequencer" "MAB_english.guide/Sequencer"
@Toc "The Effect Modules"

Sequencer
---------

@{b}ARexx template@{ub}
     P2=PROJECT2/K,P3=PROJECT3/K,
     P4=PROJECT4/K,P5=PROJECT5/K

   The @{i}Sequencer@{ui} effect module enables you to put up to five projects
together to one new project. The actual project always is the first.
The number of frames of the new project is initialized as the sum of
the frames of the selected projects.

   Just enter the numbers of the projects you want to join in the input
field inside of the graphic interface, the number of frames of the
effect project will be calculated automatically and shown to the right
of the project list.

   You can also pass the project numbers with the @{b}PROJECT2@{ub} to @{b}PROJECT5@{ub}
ARexx arguments.

   The projects dimensions must be the same, if it is not use the @{i}Scale@{ui}
module. Besides, the projects 2 to 5 must not have their own effect
modules.

   The @{i}Sequencer@{ui} effect module replaces the @{b}Append@{ub} operation of
MainActor.


@EndNode

@Node "Text" "MAB_english.guide/Text"
@Toc "The Effect Modules"

Text
----

@{b}ARexx template@{ub}
     SDIR=SCROLLDIRECTION/K,SS=SCROLLSTEPS/K

   The @{i}Text@{ui} effect module offers you to overlay your project with text
lines in various colours, fonts and alignments. The text can be
scrolled up and down like a movie end sequence.

   In the @{b}Text Lines Box@{ub} at the top of the graphic interface, you can
create copy and remove text lines with the three buttons @{b}New Line@{ub}, @{b}Copy@{ub}
and @{b}Remove@{ub}. The lines can be selected in the list to the right of these
three buttons with the mouse.

   You can change the settings of the actual text line in the @{b}Text Line
Settings Box@{ub}.  First, you can change the alignment of the text line
with the @{b}Alignment@{ub} cycle gadget. This option can be used to set the
horizontl position of the text in the line; the default value is
@{b}Centered@{ub}, that means that the line is aligned to the midle of the
screen. The two other supported alignments are @{b}Left@{ub} and @{b}Right@{ub}, the text
is displayed at the left/right side of the screen.

   You can enter the text in the @{b}Enter text@{ub} input field; new lines are
initialized with @{b}New Line@{ub}. You can also adjust the vertical distance to
the next line in the input field below. With the value 0, the next line
would be directly appended to the actual line, the value defaults to 10.

   When you activate the @{b}Select Font@{ub} button, a font requester is opened,
with which you can select your prefered font and it's height. The name
of the active font and it's height is shown in the display box to the
right of the @{b}Select Font@{ub} button.

   At last, you can adjust the colour of the font with the three input
fields @{b}Red@{ub}, @{b}Green@{ub} and @{b}Blue@{ub}. The values of all fields must be less than
255. If you adjust all three values to 0, the colour of the font is
black, if you adjust all to 255, it will be white (default).

   With the third window box, the @{b}Scroll Settings Box@{ub}, you can define if
text scrolling is active and if the text should scroll up or down.

   You can define the scoll direction :

@{b}No Scrolling@{ub}
     No scrolling is activated, the text is centered vertically to the
     middle of the screen.

@{b}Scroll up@{ub}
     The text appears at the bottom of the screen, scrolls up and
     disappears at the top of the screen. With each frame of the effect
     project, the text moves with the number of pixels defined in the
     @{b}Steps@{ub} input field (defaults to 2).

@{b}Scroll down@{ub}
     The text appears at the top of the screen, scrolls down and
     disappears at the bottom of the screen. With each frame of the
     effect project, the text moves with the number of pixels defined
     in the @{b}Steps@{ub} input field (defaults to 2).

   With a scroll mode active, MainActor Broadcast automatically adjusts
the number of frames of the effect project to the number necessary for
scrolling the text into the screen and out of the screen at the other
side.

   The @{i}Text@{ui} effect module uses private setting files to save the text
lines and their settings. The file "@{b}Text_Default.Prefs@{ub}" is the default
file; this file is loaded with the first use of the @{i}Text@{ui} effect module.
You can load and save setting files with the @{b}Load As...@{ub} and @{b}Save As...@{ub}
buttons.


@EndNode

@Node "Wipe_Squares" "MAB_english.guide/Wipe_Squares"
@Toc "The Effect Modules"

Wipe_Squares
------------

@{b}ARexx template@{ub}
     PR=PROJECTNUMBER/K,SS=SQUARESIZE/K,
     WM=WIPEMODE/K

   The @{i}Wipe_Squares@{ui} effect module enables you to create a fade between
the actual project and a selected alternative project. The screen of
the actal project is filled with squares which contain the related part
of the screen in the alternative project. When the complete screen is
filled with the squares and the destination project is totally shown,
the fade has finished.

   You can adjust the number of the destination project in the @{b}Project
Nr@{ub} input field inside of the graphic interface or pass it with the
@{b}PROJECTNUMBER@{ub} ARexx option. The destination project must have the same
width and height as the actual project.

   You can set the size of the squares in the @{b}Square Size@{ub} input field
inside of the graphic interface or pass it with the @{b}SQUARESIZE@{ub} ARexx
option.

   Besides, you can define how the squares should be inserted into the
project:

@{b}Horizontal Fill@{ub}
     With this mode, the screen is filled from the bottom to the top.
     You can activate this mode with the @{b}Horizontal Fill@{ub} radio button
     in the graphic interface or pass @{b}HORIZONTAL@{ub} to the @{b}WIPEMODE@{ub} ARexx
     option.

@{b}Vertical Fill@{ub}
     With this mode, the screen is filled from the left to the right.
     You can activate this mode with the @{b}Vertical Fill@{ub} radio button in
     the graphic interface or pass @{b}VERTICAL@{ub} to the @{b}WIPEMODE@{ub} ARexx
     option.


@EndNode

@Node "The Sound Modules" "MAB_english.guide/The Sound Modules"
@Toc "The Modules"

The Sound Modules
=================

   MainActor Broadcast has Sound Modules for the following sound
formats:

   @{b}*@{ub} AIFF

   @{b}*@{ub} FastTracker

   @{b}*@{ub} FutureComposer 1.3

   @{b}*@{ub} FutureComposer 1.4

   @{b}*@{ub} IFF-8SVX (IFF-Sample)

   @{b}*@{ub} JamCracker

   @{b}*@{ub} MED

   @{b}*@{ub} MultiTracker

   @{b}*@{ub} NoiseTracker

   @{b}*@{ub} OctaMED

   @{b}*@{ub} Octalyzer

   @{b}*@{ub} ProTracker

   @{b}*@{ub} ScreamTracker 3.0 (S3M)

   @{b}*@{ub} SidMon 2.0

   @{b}*@{ub} Sonic Arranger

   @{b}*@{ub} SoundMon 2.0

   @{b}*@{ub} SoundMon 2.2

   @{b}*@{ub} SoundTracker15

   @{b}*@{ub} SoundTracker31

   @{b}*@{ub} StarTracker4

   @{b}*@{ub} MS-Windows .WAV Format

   All of the sound formats listed above can be used with each project.
All sound modules support crunching with @{b}Powerpacker@{ub} or @{b}XPK@{ub}.

   OctaMED support was licensed by RBF Software, who has the copyright.


@EndNode

@Node "MainView Broadcast" "MAB_english.guide/MainView Broadcast"
@Toc "Main"

MainView Broadcast
******************

   MainView Broadcast is MainActor Broadcast's external player. It can
display all animations/pictures for which MainActor Broadcast has the
proper load modules.  You can simply intgrate it into file managers
like @{b}DiskMaster II@{ub} or @{b}DirectoryOpus@{ub}.

   The key commands while playing animations or showing pictures are
the same as if you would view them directly with MainActor Broadcast.
That is the reason for not listing them here again, have a look at
@{"The Control Window" Link "The Control Window"} under @{b}Play@{ub} and @{b}Show@{ub}.

   If MainActor Broadcast saved an icon for the animations/pictures to
view, MainView will take the view settings from this icon (overruling
its own settings)!

   MainView will use MainActor Broadcast's @{b}Center@{ub} option (which centers
the display of your animations or pictures) by default. If you specify
an X or Y Offset the center option will be disabled and the specified
offsets will be used instead.

   You can start MainView Broadcast from the Workbench or from the CLI.


 @{" Starting MainView Broadcast from the Workbench " Link "Starting MainView Broadcast from the Workbench"} 
 @{" Starting MainView Broadcast from the CLI " Link "Starting MainView Broadcast from the CLI"} 


@EndNode

@Node "Starting MainView Broadcast from the Workbench" "MAB_english.guide/Starting MainView Broadcast from the Workbench"
@Toc "MainView Broadcast"

Starting MainView Broadcast from the Workbench
==============================================

   If you start MainView from the Workbench (per icon), you can select
the file(s) to view in an ASL requester. For multi selecting just press
one of the shift keys and select the files with the mouse. (Starting
from OS 2.1+)

MainView supports the following tooltypes:

@{b}DisplayModule=<Module>@{ub}
     This tool type gives you the possibility to select your prefered
     display module, like Amiga, Picasso, etc. and to pass that
     information to MainView Broadcast.

@{b}DisplayType=<Number>@{ub}
     If the selected display module supports more than one display type,
     for example @{b}Intuition Window@{ub} or @{b}Intuition Screen@{ub}, you can pass your
     prefered display type to MainView Broadcast with this tool type.
     The display types in the display modules are numbered in
     lexicographic order with 1 being the first display type.

@{b}LoaderModule=<Module>@{ub}
     The default load module is the @{b}Universal@{ub} module.  You can select
     another module with this tool type.

@{b}Directory=<Path>@{ub}
     This is the initial directory for the ASL requester. The default
     value is @{b}PROGDIR:@{ub} for the directory MainView Broadcast is started
     from.

@{b}Center@{ub}
     This tool type activates the @{b}Center@{ub} option of the display modules.
     All graphic information will be aligned to the center of the
     output device (screen or window)

@{b}XOffset=<Value>@{ub}
     You can directly set the start x offset. 0 is the left border.  If
     you specify an @{b}XOffset@{ub}, centration will be disabled !

@{b}YOffset=<Value>@{ub}
     You can directly set the initial y offset. 0 is the top border.
     If you specify an @{b}YOffset@{ub}, centration will be disabled !

@{b}FrameCounter@{ub}
     @{b}FrameInfo@{ub} enables the FrameCounter option of the display modules.
     You can get the number of the actual frame from the upper right
     corner of the screen. It is disabled by default.

@{b}StopPlayback@{ub}
     This option is quite useful for recording animations on a video
     recorder.  The tool type makes the playback stop after displaying
     the first frame; you can then start recording on the video
     recorder and continue playback with the SPACE bar.

@{b}EndlessRepeat@{ub}
     This option makes MainView Broadcast play all animations
     continously.

@{b}Repeat=<Value>@{ub}
     Repeats the animation <Value> times. For example @{b}Repeat=1@{ub} would
     play the animation one time. Disables the @{b}Endless Repeat@{ub} option.

@{b}CacheData@{ub}
     Enables caching. With caching enabled, MainView plays all pictures
     and animations from the RAM disk and not directly from the
     harddisk (or whatever). If you do not have enough RAM, MainView
     Broadcast automatically disables this option and loads the data
     directly from device.


@EndNode

@Node "Starting MainView Broadcast from the CLI" "MAB_english.guide/Starting MainView Broadcast from the CLI"
@Toc "MainView Broadcast"

Starting MainView Broadcast from the CLI
========================================

   Starting MainView from the CLI will give you enhanced functionality.
You can, for example, define patterns for animations or picture lists.
The commands are identical to the tool types, so please refer to the
section @{b}Starting MainView Broadcast from the Workbench@{ub} to get details.

   Usage is :

     DM=DISPLAYMODULE/K,
     LM=LOADERMODULE/K,
     FC=FRAMECOUNTER/S,C=CENTER/S,
     XO=XOFFSET/K,YO=YOFFSET/K,
     SP=STOPPLAYBACK/S,
     CD=CACHEDATA/S,
     ER=ENDLESSREPEAT/S,R=REPEAT/K,
     DT=DISPLAYTYPE/K,F=FILES/F

   MainView Broadcast supports Amiga wildcards, for example:

@{b}MVBroadcast CD REPEAT=1 DISPLAYMODULE=PICASSO WIDTH=1024
HEIGHT=768 cd0:fli/#?.fli@{ub}.

   This example would play all files on the device cd0: , which end
with ".fli".  They would be displayed on the Picasso-II graphics board
with a resolution of 1024x768 points; the data would be cached in
memory and played only once.


@EndNode

@Node "RipAVISound" "MAB_english.guide/RipAVISound"
@Toc "Main"

RipAVISound
***********

   @{b}RipAVISound@{ub}'s task is to extract the sound information from an AVI
animation and to store it as an IFF sample or play it straight off the
animation. As default, RipAVISound stores an IFF sample onto the path
of the selected animation. The sound sample gets the base name of the
animation and the suffix ".iff". Besides, a ".Sound" file is created,
which applies the created sample to frame 1 of the animation. With the
@{b}PlayOnly@{ub} option activated, RipAVISound just plays the sound.

@{b}Starting RipAVISound from the Workbench@{ub}
     Choose the prefered animation from the ASL requester. When the
     sample was created or played, the requester automatically appears
     again. The @{b}PlayOnly@{ub} tool type activates the playback of the sound
     information. You can pass the name of the starting directory of
     the ASL requester with the @{b}Directory@{ub} tool type.

@{b}Starting RipAVISound from the CLI@{ub}
     The Usage:
          P=PLAYONLY/S,F=FILE/F

     @{b}PLAYONLY@{ub} activates playback. @{b}FILE@{ub} defines the AVI file the sound
     information should be ripped off. If RipAVISound is started
     without arguments, an ASL requester is opened to manually select
     the file.


@EndNode

@Node "PlaySound" "MAB_english.guide/PlaySound"
@Toc "Main"

PlaySound
*********

   @{b}PlaySound@{ub} is a quite simple program, it just plays a selected sound
file.  So, you do not have to start MainActor Broadcast every time you
want to test a sound file. PlaySound uses the same sound modules ad
MainActor Broadcast and so recognizes the same file types. Besides, it
uses the same options like adjusting volume or balance.

   When you start PlaySound from the Workbench, you can select your
prefered sound file with the upcoming ASL requester. The sound will be
played and afterwards, the requester appears again. You may then select
another sound file or quit the program with the @{b}Cancel@{ub} button. When you
start PlaySound from the CLI, the sound file passed as argument will be
played; you can cancel this playback with CTRL-C.

@{b}Pecularities of PlaySound:@{ub}
     When you start PlaySound from the Workbench, you can adjust some
     settings in the tool types of the icon. @{b}Volume@{ub} defines the volume
     of the sound and supports values from 0 (no sound) to 64 (louder);
     @{b}Balance@{ub} defines the balance and supports values from -64 (only
     left speaker) to 0 (both spakers) and up to +64 (only right
     speaker). You can pass the name of the starting directory of the
     ASL requester with the @{b}Directory@{ub} tool type.

@{b}The CLI usage of PlaySound@{ub}
          V=VOLUME/K,B=BALANCE/K,F=FILE/F
     @{b}VOLUME@{ub} and @{b}BALANCE@{ub} define volume and balance. @{b}FILE@{ub} defines the
     sound file to be played.


@EndNode

@Node "The ARexx Interface" "MAB_english.guide/The ARexx Interface"
@Toc "Main"

The ARexx Interface
*******************

   The default ARexx interface of MainActor Broadcast is @{b}MABROADCAST@{ub}.
Besides this global port, each project has a local port of it's own of
the form @{b}MABROADCAST.XX@{ub} with XX a number between 1 and 99, the project
number.

   You can change the name of the global ARexx port when you start
MainActor Broadcast.

   According to the two kinds of ARexx ports in MainActor Broadcast,
there are two kinds of ARexx commands:

   @{b}*@{ub} The global commands These commands can only be directed to the
     global ARexx port of MainActor Broadcast.

   @{b}*@{ub} The local commands These commands are only supported by the local
     ARexx port of the particular project.  You can get the name of the
     local port with the global @{b}GETPROJECTPORT@{ub} command.

   The syntax of the ARexx commands is described by using templates.
The templates used are compatible with the AmigaDOS template
specifications and should therefore be familiar.

The patterns are defined as following:

argument/A
     Always required. The parameter has to be included for the command
     to be accepted.

option/K
     Keyword required. The option's keyword has to be given. An example
     is @{b}PORTNAME/K@{ub}, if you want to specify the portname you can use
     @{b}PORTNAME MABROADCAST@{ub}. A simple @{b}PORTNAME@{ub} would not be allowed
     because of the missing keyword.

option/S
     Switch keyword. If the option is specified, the associated
     function is enabled, otherwise it is disabled.

option/M
     Multiple argument. You can specify any number of parameters.

option/T
     Toggle keyword. Similar to the switch keyword. The option however
     toggles from on to off or vice-versa every time it is specified.

string/F
     Final argument. The rest of the command line (including spaces) is
     used for this argument. It is therefore often used for strings and
     file paths.

=
     Shortcut. For example @{b}M=MODULE/S@{ub} allows you to enter @{b}M@{ub} instead of
     @{b}MODULE@{ub}.

   Have a look into the directory @{b}MABroadcast:Rexx@{ub} for documented ARexx
sample scripts.


 @{" The global ARexx Commands " Link "The global ARexx Commands"} 
 @{" The Project ARexx Commands " Link "The Project ARexx Commands"} 


@EndNode

@Node "The global ARexx Commands" "MAB_english.guide/The global ARexx Commands"
@Next "The Project ARexx Commands"
@Toc "The ARexx Interface"

The global ARexx Commands
=========================

   The global ARexx commands MainActor Broadcast currently supports are:


 @{" CLOSEGUI " Link "CLOSEGUI"} 
 @{" GETADDDISPLAYSETTINGS " Link "GETADDDISPLAYSETTINGS"} 
 @{" GETDISPLAYSETTINGS " Link "GETDISPLAYSETTINGS"} 
 @{" GETDISPLAYSTRINGS " Link "GETDISPLAYSTRINGS"} 
 @{" GETNUMBEROFPROJECTS " Link "GETNUMBEROFPROJECTS"} 
 @{" GETPROJECTPORT " Link "GETPROJECTPORT"} 
 @{" ICONIFY " Link "ICONIFY"} 
 @{" OPENGUI " Link "OPENGUI"} 
 @{" OPENPROJECT " Link "OPENPROJECT"} 
 @{" PRINTTEXT " Link "PRINTTEXT"} 
 @{" QUIT " Link "QUIT"} 
 @{" SAVE " Link "SAVE"} 
 @{" SCREENTOBACK " Link "SCREENTOBACK"} 
 @{" SCREENTOFRONT " Link "SCREENTOFRONT"} 
 @{" SETACTUALPROJECT " Link "SETACTUALPROJECT"} 
 @{" SETADDDISPLAYSETTINGS " Link "SETADDDISPLAYSETTINGS"} 
 @{" SETDISPLAYSETTINGS " Link "SETDISPLAYSETTINGS"} 
 @{" SETFILLBAR " Link "SETFILLBAR"} 
 @{" SETGLOBALSETTINGS " Link "SETGLOBALSETTINGS"} 


@EndNode

@Node "CLOSEGUI" "MAB_english.guide/CLOSEGUI"
@Toc "The global ARexx Commands"

CLOSEGUI
--------

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     None

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Close the GUI (graphic User Interface)

@{b}Description:@{ub}
     If the MainActor Broadcasts graphical user interface (GUI) is
     open, you can close it with this command. An icon will be
     positioned on the Workbench screen. You can reactivate the GUI
     with the @{b}OPENGUI@{ub} command or simply by double clicking on the icon.

     A deactivated GUI will allow you to use MainActor Broadcast as an
     ARexx server; in this state MainActor Broadcast is only able to
     process ARexx commands and scripts.


@EndNode

@Node "GETADDDISPLAYSETTINGS" "MAB_english.guide/GETADDDISPLAYSETTINGS"
@Toc "The global ARexx Commands"

GETADDDISPLAYSETTINGS
---------------------

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     R=REPEAT/S,C=CENTER/S,
     XO=XOFFSET/S,YO=YOFFSET/S,
     SP=STOPPLAYBACK/S,
     FC=FRAMECOUNTER/S,
     EXP=EXTERNALPALETTE/S,
     DITHER/S

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Get the additional display window settings

@{b}Description:@{ub}
     For each setting specified, a result text will be appended to the
     @{b}RESULT@{ub} variable.  The @{b}REPEAT@{ub} switch will return @{b}ENDLESS@{ub} or the
     number of repeats selected for the repeat setting. The @{b}CENTER@{ub},
     @{b}STOPPLAYBACK@{ub} and @{b}FRAMECOUNTER@{ub} options will either return @{b}ON@{ub} or
     @{b}OFF@{ub}, depending on the setting being enabled or disabled.  The
     @{b}XOFFSET@{ub} and @{b}YOFFSET@{ub} options will return the x and y offset values.
     The @{b}DITHER@{ub} option returns the selected dither algorithm.

     You can set the additonal display settings with the
     @{b}SETADDDISPLAYSETTINGS@{ub} command.


@EndNode

@Node "GETDISPLAYSETTINGS" "MAB_english.guide/GETDISPLAYSETTINGS"
@Toc "The global ARexx Commands"

GETDISPLAYSETTINGS
------------------

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     M=MODULE/S,L=LOCK/S,T=TYPE/S,
     MODE/S,W=WIDTH/S,H=HEIGHT/S,
     S=SPECIAL/S,D=DEPTH/S,
     MD=MAXDEPTH/S

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Get the display window settings

@{b}Description:@{ub}
     For each setting specified, a result text will be appended to the
     @{b}RESULT@{ub} variable. The options are identical to those described in
     the @{b}SETDISPLAYSETTINGS@{ub} command. You can always get the settings of
     the @{b}MODULE@{ub} and @{b}LOCK@{ub} options, all other options need a loaded project.

     For example:

     "GETDISPLAYSETTINGS MODULE LOCK MODE WIDTH HEIGHT DEPTH MAXDEPTH"
     could return "Amiga ON 2048 320 200 1 6 6" which would mean, that
     the display module is the Amiga module, that lock is on, the
     ModeID is 2048 (LORES HAM), the width and height of the display is
     320 and 200 and that the current and max depth is 6.


@EndNode

@Node "GETDISPLAYSTRINGS" "MAB_english.guide/GETDISPLAYSTRINGS"
@Toc "The global ARexx Commands"

GETDISPLAYSTRINGS
-----------------

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     T=TYPE/S,MODE/S,S=SPECIAL/S

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Get the strings of the display settings.

@{b}Description:@{ub}
     The @{b}SETDISPLAYSETTINGS@{ub} command has one disadvantage, it will only
     return the decimal numbers of the current @{b}TYPE@{ub}, @{b}MODE@{ub} and @{b}SPECIAL@{ub}
     settings. Sometimes it is however useful to know the real name of
     a ModeID or display type. This can be done with this command. The
     result string will be returned in the ARexx @{b}RESULT@{ub} variable. Only
     pass one option at one time, the @{b}TYPE@{ub} and @{b}SPECIAL@{ub} options also
     need a loaded project while you can always use the @{b}MODE@{ub} option to
     get the name of the specified ModeID.


@EndNode

@Node "GETNUMBEROFPROJECTS" "MAB_english.guide/GETNUMBEROFPROJECTS"
@Toc "The global ARexx Commands"

GETNUMBEROFPROJECTS
-------------------

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     None

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Get the snumber of projects.

@{b}Description:@{ub}
     This command returns the number of actually loaded projects in the
     ARexx @{b}RESULT@{ub} variable.


@EndNode

@Node "GETPROJECTPORT" "MAB_english.guide/GETPROJECTPORT"
@Toc "The global ARexx Commands"

GETPROJECTPORT
--------------

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     N=NUMBER/K,NAME/F

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Get the name of a project's ARexx port

@{b}Description:@{ub}
     Using this command, you can find out the name of the project ARexx
     port for each actually loaded project. The name of the ARexx port
     will be returned in the @{b}RESULT@{ub} variable. You can simply specify
     the project by its name if you use the @{b}NAME@{ub} option. You can see
     the name of a project in the titlebar of the project window.
     However, we recommend to use the @{b}NUMBER@{ub} option as several projects
     can have the same name but not the same project number (for example
     if you have loaded the same animation several times). You can find
     out the number of a project in the titlebar of the project window.

     If no project is specified the name of the ARexx port of the
     actual project will be returned.


@EndNode

@Node "ICONIFY" "MAB_english.guide/ICONIFY"
@Toc "The global ARexx Commands"

ICONIFY
-------

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     None

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Iconify MainActor Broadcast.

@{b}Description:@{ub}
     @{b}ICONIFY@{ub} closes the GUI and places an icon on the Workbench.
     MainActor Broadcast is able to receive and process ARexx commands
     and scripts in this state. You can reactivate the GUI with the
     @{b}OPENGUI@{ub} command or simply by double clicking on the icon.

     For futher explaination have a look at @{b}CLOSEGUI@{ub}.


@EndNode

@Node "OPENGUI" "MAB_english.guide/OPENGUI"
@Toc "The global ARexx Commands"

OPENGUI
-------

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     None

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Open the GUI (graphic User Interface)

@{b}Description:@{ub}
     If the GUI (graphic User Interface) is closed, you can open it
     with this command.


@EndNode

@Node "OPENPROJECT" "MAB_english.guide/OPENPROJECT"
@Toc "The global ARexx Commands"

OPENPROJECT
-----------

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     FR=FILEREQ/S,CD=CACHEDATA/S,M=MODULE/K,
     LP=LASTPICTURE/K,NAME/F

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Open a new project

@{b}Description:@{ub}
     This command enables you to load a project, even if the GUI of
     MainActor Broadcast is currently closed. If you specify the
     @{b}FILEREQ@{ub} option, you will be able to select the file with an
     ASL requester. The other method to specify a file is to use the
     @{b}NAME@{ub} argument, which allows a complete file name to be specified
     directly. If you want the loaded data to be cached in memory use
     the @{b}CACHEDATA@{ub} switch.  In general, @{b}OPENPROJECT@{ub} uses the Universal
     module. You can choose another module with the @{b}MODULE@{ub} option. If
     you have enabled the picture list option of MainActor Broadcast,
     you are able to load a whole list of pictures with the picture
     modules. In that case the @{b}LASTPICTURE@{ub} option specifies the last
     picture in the list and the @{b}NAME@{ub} option the first one.


@EndNode

@Node "PRINTTEXT" "MAB_english.guide/PRINTTEXT"
@Toc "The global ARexx Commands"

PRINTTEXT
---------

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     B=BUFFER/S,TEXT/F

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Print a text in the Text Buffer Window

@{b}Description:@{ub}
     @{b}PRINTTEXT@{ub} prints the specified text string in the @{i}Text Buffer
     Window@{ui}.  If you enable the @{b}BUFFER@{ub} switch, the text will be
     buffered, that means it will not be overwritten by the next text
     which is printed in the window and is permanently stored (until
     you quit MainActor Broadcast or clear the buffer).


@EndNode

@Node "QUIT" "MAB_english.guide/QUIT"
@Toc "The global ARexx Commands"

QUIT
----

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     None

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Close all projects and quit MainActor Broadcast

@{b}Description:@{ub}
     The @{b}QUIT@{ub} command is very straight forward, it instantly closes all
     projects and the GUI (if open).


@EndNode

@Node "SAVE" "MAB_english.guide/SAVE"
@Toc "The global ARexx Commands"

SAVE
----

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     M=MODULE/K

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Save your projects.

@{b}Description:@{ub}
     @{b}SAVE@{ub} saves all selected frames of your actual project in the
     desired file format. You can pass the name of this format with the
     @{b}MODULE@{ub} option.


@EndNode

@Node "SCREENTOBACK" "MAB_english.guide/SCREENTOBACK"
@Toc "The global ARexx Commands"

SCREENTOBACK
------------

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     None

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Switch the MainActor Broadcast screen to the back

@{b}Description:@{ub}
     This command switches the screen, on which MainActor Broadcast has
     opened its GUI, to the back.


@EndNode

@Node "SCREENTOFRONT" "MAB_english.guide/SCREENTOFRONT"
@Toc "The global ARexx Commands"

SCREENTOFRONT
-------------

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     None

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Switch the MainActor Broadcast screen to the front

@{b}Description:@{ub}
     This command switches the screen, on which MainActor Broadcast has
     opened its GUI, to the front.


@EndNode

@Node "SETACTUALPROJECT" "MAB_english.guide/SETACTUALPROJECT"
@Toc "The global ARexx Commands"

SETACTUALPROJECT
----------------

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     SW=SWITCHRIGHT/S,SL=SWITCHLEFT/S

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Set the actual project

@{b}Description:@{ub}
     You can set the actual project, the project which is visible in
     the @{i}Project Window@{ui}, with this command. The @{b}SWITCHRIGHT@{ub} and
     @{b}SWITCHLEFT@{ub} options have the same effect, as if you klick on the
     left or right arrow gadget in the @{i}Project Window@{ui}: The project with
     the next higher or lower number will be selected.


@EndNode

@Node "SETADDDISPLAYSETTINGS" "MAB_english.guide/SETADDDISPLAYSETTINGS"
@Toc "The global ARexx Commands"

SETADDDISPLAYSETTINGS
---------------------

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     R=REPEAT/K,C=CENTER/S,
     XO=XOFFSET/K,YO=YOFFSET/K,
     SP=STOPPLAYBACK/K,
     FC=FRAMECOUNTER/K,
     EXP=EXTERNALPALETTE/K,
     DITHER/K

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Set the additional display window settings.

@{b}Description:@{ub}
     Set the settings of the additional display settings window with
     this command. The @{b}CENTER@{ub} switch turns centerin on, you are able to
     specify the x and y offset with the @{b}XOFFSET@{ub} and @{b}YOFFSET@{ub} options,
     they will automatically disable the @{b}CENTER@{ub} setting. If you pass
     @{b}ENDLESS@{ub} to the @{b}REPEAT@{ub} option, the endless repeat setting will be
     enabled.  If you want to specify, how often a project shall be
     played, just pass the number of repetitions to it, the endless
     repeat setting will then be automatically disabled. You can pass
     @{b}ON@{ub}, @{b}OFF@{ub} or @{b}TOGGLE@{ub} to the @{b}FRAMECOUNTER@{ub}, @{b}STOPPLAYBACK@{ub} and
     @{b}EXTERNALPALETTE@{ub} options, which will enable, disable or toggle the
     @{b}Frame Counter@{ub}, @{b}Stop Playback@{ub} and @{b}External Palette@{ub} setting. You can
     pass @{b}NONE@{ub} to the @{b}DITHER@{ub} option to disable dithering or the name of
     the prefered dither mode, for example @{b}FLOYD@{ub} for Floyd-Steinberg
     dithering.

@{b}Example:@{ub}
     SETADDDISPLAYSETTINGS REPEAT 1 FRAMECOUNTER ON STOPPLAYBACK ON
     CENTER


@EndNode

@Node "SETDISPLAYSETTINGS" "MAB_english.guide/SETDISPLAYSETTINGS"
@Toc "The global ARexx Commands"

SETDISPLAYSETTINGS
------------------

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     M=MODULE/K,L=LOCK/K,T=TYPE/K,
     MODE/K,W=WIDTH/K,
     H=HEIGHT/K,S=SPECIAL/K,
     D=DEPTH/K,MD=MAXDEPTH/S

@{b}Description:@{ub}
     This command will allow you to specify the settings of the display
     window.  The @{b}MODULE@{ub} and @{b}LOCK@{ub} options are always settable, all other
     options need a loaded project. You can select a new display module
     with the @{b}MODULE@{ub} option, for example @{b}Picasso@{ub}. If the display module
     does not exist or cannot be opened, the @{b}Amiga@{ub} display module will
     be set.  If you pass @{b}ON@{ub} to the @{b}LOCK@{ub} option, the @{b}Lock Attributes@{ub}
     setting will be enabled, if you pass @{b}OFF@{ub} it will be disabled. You
     can toggle the @{b}Lock Attributes@{ub} setting with @{b}TOGGLE@{ub}.

     Some display modules, like the @{b}Amiga@{ub} module, do support more than
     one display type. You can set the current display type with this
     option. Just specify the number of the display type starting with
     one. The @{b}Amiga@{ub} module, for example, supports the following display
     types:

       1. Full screen display

       2. Intuition screen display

       3. Intuition window

     If you use the @{b}Amiga@{ub} module you can use this option to set the
     ModeID of the display.  The ModeID has to be a decimal or hex
     number. If you use hex numbers, they should start with a leading
     0x. Please have a look into the Commodore Include files to find
     out the exact values for the modes you wish to set. The example
     given below would set a @{b}LORES HAM@{ub} intuition screen.

     The modules for graphic boards (like the @{b}Picasso@{ub} display module)
     use the @{b}WIDTH@{ub} and @{b}HEIGHT@{ub} options for specifying the exact display
     mode unlike the @{b}Amiga@{ub} module, which uses the ModeID.

     Some display modules are able to use more than one colour mode.
     For example, the @{b}Amiga@{ub} display module has several special modes
     like @{b}EHB@{ub} and @{b}HAM@{ub}, which can be set with the @{b}SPECIAL@{ub} option. Just
     specify the number of the colour mode (starting from one) to
     change the current colour mode.  Most display modules however only
     support one mode.

     Set the depth of the display with the @{b}DEPTH@{ub} option. Common values
     are in the range of 1-8 (2-256 colours) for the @{b}Amiga@{ub} display,
     graphic boards can mostly also display bit depth of 16 (65.536
     colours) and 24 (16.777.216 colours).

     The @{b}MAXDEPTH@{ub} option sets the depth to the maximum value possible
     for the current display mode.

@{b}Examples:@{ub}
     SETDISPLAYSETTINGS MODULE Amiga TYPE 2 MODE 0x800
     SETDISPLAYSETTINGS MODULE Picasso WIDTH 640 HEIGHT 480


@EndNode

@Node "SETFILLBAR" "MAB_english.guide/SETFILLBAR"
@Toc "The global ARexx Commands"

SETFILLBAR
----------

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     PR=PROCESS/K,CLEAR/S

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Set the fillbar in the text buffer window to a given value

@{b}Description:@{ub}
     The @{b}PROCESS@{ub} keyword is used to set the length of the fillbar in
     the @{i}Text Buffer Window@{ui}. Valid values are in the range of 0 to 100.
     If you specify a value smaller than 0 or greater than 100 or
     specify the @{b}CLEAR@{ub} switch, the fillbar will be cleared and
     disabled. If the user did hit the @{b}CANCEL@{ub} gadget of the fillbar,
     the ARexx variable @{b}RESULT@{ub} will be set to 5.

     Note that the GUI is locked while a value is displayed in the
     fillbar. You have to clear it before the GUI is unlocked (useable)
     again.

@{b}Example:@{ub}
     SETFILLBAR PROCESS 35


@EndNode

@Node "SETGLOBALSETTINGS" "MAB_english.guide/SETGLOBALSETTINGS"
@Toc "The global ARexx Commands"

SETGLOBALSETTINGS
-----------------

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     PL=PICTURELISTS/K,PS=PICTURESORT/K,
     CI=CREATEINDEX/K

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Set the global settings

@{b}Description:@{ub}
     You can set the global settings of MainActor Broadcast, which are
     the contents of the @{b}Settings Menu@{ub}, with this command. The
     @{b}CREATEINDEX@{ub} and @{b}PICTURELIST@{ub} options expect @{b}ON@{ub}, @{b}OFF@{ub} or @{b}TOGGLE@{ub} to
     enable, disable or toggle the corresponding setting.

     You can set the picture sort mode by passing @{b}INVERSE@{ub} or @{b}NORMAL@{ub} to
     the @{b}PICTURESORT@{ub} option.


@EndNode

@Node "The Project ARexx Commands" "MAB_english.guide/The Project ARexx Commands"
@Prev "The global ARexx Commands"
@Toc "The ARexx Interface"

The Project ARexx Commands
==========================

   MainActor Broadcasts projects support the following ARexx commands.


 @{" DESELECTALL " Link "DESELECTALL"} 
 @{" DESELECTRANGE " Link "DESELECTRANGE"} 
 @{" EFFECT " Link "EFFECT"} 
 @{" GETFRAMEINFO " Link "GETFRAMEINFO"} 
 @{" GETPROJECTINFO " Link "GETPROJECTINFO"} 
 @{" PLAYPROJECT " Link "PLAYPROJECT"} 
 @{" SELECTALL " Link "SELECTALL"} 
 @{" SELECTRANGE " Link "SELECTRANGE"} 
 @{" SETACCESSMODE " Link "SETACCESSMODE"} 
 @{" SETTIMECODE " Link "SETTIMECODE"} 
 @{" SHOWPROJECT " Link "SHOWPROJECT"} 


@EndNode

@Node "DESELECTALL" "MAB_english.guide/DESELECTALL"
@Toc "The Project ARexx Commands"

DESELECTALL
-----------

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     None

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Deselect all frames

@{b}Description:@{ub}
     Deselect all frames in the project.


@EndNode

@Node "DESELECTRANGE" "MAB_english.guide/DESELECTRANGE"
@Toc "The Project ARexx Commands"

DESELECTRANGE
-------------

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     F=FROM/K,T=TO/K

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Deselect range of frames

@{b}Description:@{ub}
     Deselect all frames between the the two frames specified by @{b}FROM@{ub}
     and @{b}TO@{ub}.


@EndNode

@Node "EFFECT" "MAB_english.guide/EFFECT"
@Toc "The Project ARexx Commands"

EFFECT
------

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     MODULE/K, ...

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Sets an effect module for the current project.

@{b}Description:@{ub}
     This command enables you to apply an effect module to the current
     project. The name of the effect module must be passed with the
     @{b}MODULE@{ub} option. If the effect module had not been enabled, it will
     be activated; otherwise, only the new options will be passed to
     the effect module. If another effect module had been selected for
     the actual project, it is removed from memory and the new effect
     module is enabled.

     You must always use the @{b}MODULE@{ub} option !

     You have to give the options of the effect module directly after
     the @{b}MODULE@{ub} option itself; they will then be passed to the effect
     module.

     The example below would activate the @{i}Scale@{ui} effect module and apply
     various size settings. For a detailed description of the effect
     modules refer to chapter @{i}The Effect Modules@{ui}.

@{b}Example:@{ub}
     MODULE SCALE SCALEWIDTH 400 SCALEHEIGHT 200 PERCENTINCREASE 2


@EndNode

@Node "GETFRAMEINFO" "MAB_english.guide/GETFRAMEINFO"
@Toc "The Project ARexx Commands"

GETFRAMEINFO
------------

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     F=FRAME/K,DS=DATASIZE/S,
     CM=COMPRESSMETHOD/S,
     CP=COLORPALETTE/S,T=TIMECODE/S

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Get information about a specific frame.

@{b}Description:@{ub}
     For each parameter specified, a result text will be appended to
     the @{b}RESULT@{ub} variable.  You have to specify a frame with the @{b}FRAME@{ub}
     option to use this command. @{b}DATASIZE@{ub} returns the size of the
     frame, @{b}COMPRESSMETHOD@{ub} the compression method and @{b}COLORPALLETE@{ub}
     returns @{b}YES@{ub} if the frame contains a colour palette or @{b}NO@{ub} if not.
     @{b}TIMECODE@{ub} returns the timecode (in 60th seconds) of the frame.


@EndNode

@Node "GETPROJECTINFO" "MAB_english.guide/GETPROJECTINFO"
@Toc "The Project ARexx Commands"

GETPROJECTINFO
--------------

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     M=MODULE/S,W=WIDTH/S,H=HEIGHT/S,
     F=FRAMES/S,LF=LOOPFRAMES/S,
     C=COLORS/S,
     SF=SPECIALFLAGS/S,
     GF=GRAPHICFORMAT/S,
     S=SIZE/S,
     CP=COLORPALETTES/S

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Get information about the project

@{b}Description:@{ub}
     @{b}GETPROJECTINFO@{ub} returns special information about the actual
     project in the ARexx variable @{b}RESULT@{ub}. The values returned are
     exactly the same as those in the @{i}Project Information Window@{ui}. The
     @{b}MODULE@{ub} switch will return the name of the display module, which is
     in use for this project, the @{b}WIDTH@{ub} and @{b}HEIGHT@{ub} switches return the
     width and height of the project; @{b}FRAMES@{ub} returns the number of
     frames, @{b}LOOPFRAMES@{ub} the number of frames used for the loop. @{b}COLORS@{ub}
     returns the amount of colours used, @{b}SPECIALFLAGS@{ub} the special
     colour mode (if any) of the project.  @{b}GRAPHICFORMAT@{ub} returns the
     format the graphic is stored in, mostly @{i}Bitmap@{ui} or @{i}Chunky-Pixel@{ui},
     @{b}SIZE@{ub} the size of the project in bytes. @{b}COLORPALLETES@{ub} will return
     the number of colour palettes in the project.


@EndNode

@Node "PLAYPROJECT" "MAB_english.guide/PLAYPROJECT"
@Toc "The Project ARexx Commands"

PLAYPROJECT
-----------

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     M=MODULE/K

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Play the project

@{b}Description:@{ub}
     Plays the project. If the display settings are locked, the display
     settings will be taken from the @{i}Display Settings Window@{ui}. If not,
     the settings will be taken directly from the project itself,
     except the name of the display module, which will be always taken
     from the @{i}Display Settings Window@{ui}. You can change this behaviour by
     specifying the display module name directly with the @{b}MODULE@{ub} option.


@EndNode

@Node "SELECTALL" "MAB_english.guide/SELECTALL"
@Toc "The Project ARexx Commands"

SELECTALL
---------

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     None

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Select all frames

@{b}Description:@{ub}
     Select all frames in the project.


@EndNode

@Node "SELECTRANGE" "MAB_english.guide/SELECTRANGE"
@Toc "The Project ARexx Commands"

SELECTRANGE
-----------

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     F=FROM/K,T=TO/K

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Select range of frames

@{b}Description:@{ub}
     Select all frames between the the two frames specified by @{b}FROM@{ub} and
     @{b}TO@{ub}.


@EndNode

@Node "SETACCESSMODE" "MAB_english.guide/SETACCESSMODE"
@Toc "The Project ARexx Commands"

SETACCESSMODE
-------------

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     RAM/S,DEVICE/S,TOGGLE/S

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Set the access mode for the project

@{b}Description:@{ub}
     @{b}SETACCESSMODE@{ub} sets the access mode for the actual project. The @{b}RAM@{ub}
     option will force the access mode to the RAM mode, the @{b}DEVICE@{ub}
     option to the device mode. The @{b}TOGGLE@{ub} option will switch the
     current state of the access mode.


@EndNode

@Node "SETTIMECODE" "MAB_english.guide/SETTIMECODE"
@Toc "The Project ARexx Commands"

SETTIMECODE
-----------

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     TC=TIMECODE/K

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Set the timecode for all selected frames

@{b}Description:@{ub}
     You can specify the timecode for a single frame or a range of
     frames, just select the frames and pass the appropriate timecode
     to the @{b}TIMECODE@{ub} option. The timecode will be set for all selected
     frames. If the animation only supports the global timecode, this
     one will be set to the passed value. This command, however, only
     works for animation formats which support timecodes.


@EndNode

@Node "SHOWPROJECT" "MAB_english.guide/SHOWPROJECT"
@Toc "The Project ARexx Commands"

SHOWPROJECT
-----------

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     M=MODULE/K

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Show the pictures or frames of the project

@{b}Description:@{ub}
     The options and behaviour of this command are exactly the same as
     those of the @{b}PLAYPROJECT@{ub} command, the project will just not be
     played. but the selected frames will be shown.


@EndNode

@Node "Tips and Tricks" "MAB_english.guide/Tips and Tricks"
@Toc "Main"

Tips and Tricks
***************

   @{b}*@{ub} Remember that very often the project's graphic format is not the
     same as that of the display module and conversion takes time. All
     display modules except the @{b}Amiga@{ub} display module are chunky-pixel
     oriented; so you better convert your bitmap based animations to a
     chunky-pixel format, best of all to that, which carries the name
     of your graphic board. So, Picasso users should use the @{b}Picasso@{ub}
     display module and the Picasso animation format, Amiga users
     without graphic board should use the @{b}Amiga@{ub} display module and the
     IFF-Anim5/7/8 animation formats. Of course, these are only
     recommendations; each animation can be played on each screen, but
     the examples stated above are the fastest choice.

   @{b}*@{ub} If you use the IFF-Anim7_16 or IFF-Anim8_16 animation savers,
     remember that the source frames should have a width, which is
     divideable by 16!  The same for the IFF-Anim7_32 and IFF-Anim8_32
     savers which need a width, which is divideable by 32. If you
     ignore this, you will get a small area to the right of your screen
     which is not updated correctly.


@EndNode

@Node "Glossary" "MAB_english.guide/Glossary"
@Toc "Main"

Glossary
********

@{b}8/16/24 Bit@{ub}
     Defines the colour depth of an animation. 8 bit is equivalent to
     256 colours, 16 bit to 65.536 colours (65K) and 24 bit to
     16.777.217 (16M) colours. This expression comes from the bitplanes
     and describes, how many bitplanes are necessary to get the
     prefered amount of colours. So, 1 bitplane can display 2 colours,
     2 bitplanes up to 4 and n bitplanes 2^n.

@{b}Bitmap@{ub}
     A bitmap is the memory, which stores the graphic information of a
     picture. You can define two kinds of bitmaps: chunky-pixel or
     bitmap oriented. On the Amiga, people often use the bitmap
     formats; with that, the bitmap is divided into several bit planes,
     which are stored one behind the other. Now, each bit, which is
     located at the same place of the bitmaps, is written one behind
     the other to define the colour of the related pixel.  This display
     mode is a little bit more complicated than the chunky-pixel mode,
     but has it's advantages in displaying animated objects.

@{b}chunky-pixel@{ub}
     In a chunky-pixel format, the bitmaps are built from bytes, which
     define directly the colour of the related pixel. This is the
     opposite from the bitplane based format used on the Amiga.

@{b}Double-Buffering@{ub}
     An animation always decompresses to two seperated bitmaps, which
     are alternately displayed after the decompression. In each case,
     the bitmap currently not visible is updated, while the other
     bitmap is shown. This procedure has the advantage, that you cannot
     see the graphic update and the animation runs smoother. Nearly all
     IFF animation formats like IFF-Anim5/7/8 are double buffering
     formats.

@{b}Color Palette@{ub}
     A colour palette is a table of colours used in the related
     picture. Color palettes are only used, if the picture has less
     than 256 colours (up to 8 bit). Pictures or animations with 16 or
     24 bit do not need a colour palette.

@{b}Loop Animation@{ub}
     A loop animation is an animation with one or two additional frames
     at the end, which manage the transition between the last (last
     two) and the first (the first two) frames. Because the first frame
     of an animation is always saved as the complete picture, while all
     other frames are saved as the difference between the previous
     frame and the actual frame, the creation of loop frames stops the
     first frame from being loaded again as complete picture.  Double
     buffering animations like the IFF animation formats always have two
     loop frames, while single buffering formats like FLI/FLC only have
     one loop frame.

@{b}Single-Buffering@{ub}
     An animation always decompresses it's data to the same bitmap, so
     you can see in some situations, how the screen is updated,
     especially if the colour palette is also changed. FLI/FLC/DL are
     single buffering formats, IFF anim brush, too.

@{b}Timecode@{ub}
     The timecode of a frame describes, how long this frame should be
     displayed at playback of the animation. MainActor Broadcast stores
     this data in 1/60 second intervals; so, a time code of 1/60
     displays the frame for 1/60 sec, while a time code of 60/60
     displays it for one second. Some animation formats only support
     one time code for the whole animation, which means, that all
     frames have the same time display length. These time codes are
     called global time codes, while local time codes are only related
     to one frame.


@EndNode

